WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:03.360 --> 00:00:04.840
BRIAN FITZPATRICK: My name
is Brian Fitzpatrick.

00:00:04.840 --> 00:00:06.540
Most people know me as Fitz.

00:00:06.540 --> 00:00:07.840
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN: And my name
is Ben Collins-Sussman.

00:00:07.840 --> 00:00:09.990
Most people call me Ben
Collins-Sussman.

00:00:09.990 --> 00:00:12.200
BRIAN FITZPATRICK: And we're
here to talk about working

00:00:12.200 --> 00:00:13.950
with human beings.

00:00:13.950 --> 00:00:15.810
A couple little notes,
first of all.

00:00:15.810 --> 00:00:19.690
We're using the experimental
service called SpeakerMeter so

00:00:19.690 --> 00:00:22.430
that you can talk all about
this show on the

00:00:22.430 --> 00:00:22.930
SpeakerMeter site.

00:00:22.930 --> 00:00:24.590
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN: As we
speak, you can rate us up and

00:00:24.590 --> 00:00:26.000
down, which could be
very exciting.

00:00:26.000 --> 00:00:26.490
BRIAN FITZPATRICK: Exactly.

00:00:26.490 --> 00:00:29.430
So good or for bad, we would
love to hear feedback.

00:00:29.430 --> 00:00:33.010
But thanks to everyone for
coming to this live taping of

00:00:33.010 --> 00:00:34.800
the Ben and Fitz show.

00:00:34.800 --> 00:00:38.640
As all of you hopefully know,
we talk a lot about things

00:00:38.640 --> 00:00:42.590
related to working with people
in computer science, in

00:00:42.590 --> 00:00:44.280
software engineering.

00:00:44.280 --> 00:00:46.570
Human beings, otherwise known
as a giant pile of

00:00:46.570 --> 00:00:47.370
intermittent bugs.

00:00:47.370 --> 00:00:48.830
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN: Right.

00:00:48.830 --> 00:00:50.480
Good way to put it.

00:00:50.480 --> 00:00:53.640
Really, probably one of the
hardest things that we don't

00:00:53.640 --> 00:00:56.000
acknowledge about writing
software is having to work

00:00:56.000 --> 00:00:56.730
with other people.

00:00:56.730 --> 00:00:56.940
Right?

00:00:56.940 --> 00:00:59.840
We study and study how to use
our languages and our

00:00:59.840 --> 00:01:01.980
compilers, and then you get
to sitting down to writing

00:01:01.980 --> 00:01:04.599
software with other people, and
you discover that they are

00:01:04.599 --> 00:01:06.740
in the way as much as the
programming language, or

00:01:06.740 --> 00:01:07.480
perhaps more.

00:01:07.480 --> 00:01:07.710
BRIAN FITZPATRICK: Right.

00:01:07.710 --> 00:01:09.880
Well, the social stuff is
really hard, right?

00:01:09.880 --> 00:01:12.740
It's more squishy, it's a
lot less deterministic.

00:01:12.740 --> 00:01:15.830
I mean, your compiler is
incredibly consistent.

00:01:15.830 --> 00:01:17.480
It's going to do the same thing,
no matter what kind of

00:01:17.480 --> 00:01:19.560
garbage you throw at it.

00:01:19.560 --> 00:01:21.820
Go ahead.

00:01:21.820 --> 00:01:22.310
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN:
If you want to be

00:01:22.310 --> 00:01:23.400
a successful engineer--

00:01:23.400 --> 00:01:25.620
this is what we tell our
friends, we tell our family.

00:01:25.620 --> 00:01:27.690
If you want to ship software
and be really good at

00:01:27.690 --> 00:01:30.390
engineering, you need to also
focus on the social, and not

00:01:30.390 --> 00:01:30.800
just the technical.

00:01:30.800 --> 00:01:32.250
BRIAN FITZPATRICK: But it's also
key to being an efficient

00:01:32.250 --> 00:01:34.970
engineer, so you don't waste a
lot of your energy bickering

00:01:34.970 --> 00:01:37.240
and arguing and yelling, et
cetera, that sort of thing.

00:01:37.240 --> 00:01:38.930
So let's get started here.

00:01:38.930 --> 00:01:41.030
We're going to talk about--

00:01:41.030 --> 00:01:43.790
there's four main areas that
we're going to focus on in the

00:01:43.790 --> 00:01:45.410
show today.

00:01:45.410 --> 00:01:45.680
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN:
By the way.

00:01:45.680 --> 00:01:47.150
We're not actual doctors.

00:01:47.150 --> 00:01:47.410
We should put that out.

00:01:47.410 --> 00:01:49.390
BRIAN FITZPATRICK: We're
not actual doctors or

00:01:49.390 --> 00:01:51.060
chemists of any sort.

00:01:51.060 --> 00:01:52.810
These are just remarkably
comfortable, and we think

00:01:52.810 --> 00:01:55.270
everyone's going to be wearing
white in the future.

00:01:55.270 --> 00:01:57.910
So to start off, we have four
different areas we're going to

00:01:57.910 --> 00:01:58.310
talk about.

00:01:58.310 --> 00:02:00.370
One is just general personal
behaviors, right?

00:02:00.370 --> 00:02:02.170
You sort of have to get
an idea of, how

00:02:02.170 --> 00:02:03.300
do you like to work?

00:02:03.300 --> 00:02:05.400
What are you good at working
with other people, and where

00:02:05.400 --> 00:02:06.820
are you bad, and that
sort of thing?

00:02:06.820 --> 00:02:07.890
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN: And then
we're going to talk about

00:02:07.890 --> 00:02:11.306
social dynamics of being
honest-- oops,

00:02:11.306 --> 00:02:14.230
did we lose a mic?

00:02:14.230 --> 00:02:15.140
BRIAN FITZPATRICK:
Check, check.

00:02:15.140 --> 00:02:15.950
Did you turn your mic off?

00:02:15.950 --> 00:02:16.830
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN: I
turned my mic off.

00:02:16.830 --> 00:02:17.580
BRIAN FITZPATRICK:
OK, talk's over.

00:02:17.580 --> 00:02:18.610
Thank you for coming.

00:02:18.610 --> 00:02:20.190
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN: You
just talk while I--

00:02:20.190 --> 00:02:20.690
BRIAN FITZPATRICK:
Oh, there you go.

00:02:20.690 --> 00:02:22.000
You're back on.

00:02:22.000 --> 00:02:22.700
OK.

00:02:22.700 --> 00:02:23.170
All right.

00:02:23.170 --> 00:02:23.970
Well done.

00:02:23.970 --> 00:02:24.470
OK.

00:02:24.470 --> 00:02:25.190
Number two.

00:02:25.190 --> 00:02:26.290
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN: Number two,
we're going to talk about

00:02:26.290 --> 00:02:28.800
the social dynamics of
being on a team.

00:02:28.800 --> 00:02:31.170
This is, how do you interoperate
with your team,

00:02:31.170 --> 00:02:32.800
how do they interoperate
with you.

00:02:32.800 --> 00:02:34.160
BRIAN FITZPATRICK: And next,
we're going to talk about how

00:02:34.160 --> 00:02:37.280
your team operates with outside
contributors, or folks

00:02:37.280 --> 00:02:40.180
that work with you that are
not in your core team.

00:02:40.180 --> 00:02:42.160
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN: But may
work closely with you.

00:02:42.160 --> 00:02:42.720
BRIAN FITZPATRICK: Exactly.

00:02:42.720 --> 00:02:43.890
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN: And then
finally, we're going to talk

00:02:43.890 --> 00:02:46.480
how you interact with other
people who are not on your

00:02:46.480 --> 00:02:48.840
team at all, probably
your users.

00:02:48.840 --> 00:02:50.700
Probably the most important
group you need to work with at

00:02:50.700 --> 00:02:51.660
some point.

00:02:51.660 --> 00:02:53.000
BRIAN FITZPATRICK: So we're glad
to have all of you here

00:02:53.000 --> 00:02:55.160
today on this live,
taped show.

00:02:55.160 --> 00:02:56.540
We're going to go to
the phones now

00:02:56.540 --> 00:02:57.860
and take some calls.

00:02:57.860 --> 00:03:00.410
We're going to start with some
questions, possibly work with

00:03:00.410 --> 00:03:03.240
the way that you sort of work
with your team, or the way

00:03:03.240 --> 00:03:04.750
you're sort of used to
working, et cetera.

00:03:04.750 --> 00:03:05.010
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN: Yeah.

00:03:05.010 --> 00:03:07.400
So questions about personal
behavior.

00:03:07.400 --> 00:03:08.640
BRIAN FITZPATRICK:
We have a caller.

00:03:08.640 --> 00:03:10.330
We got Harlan from Kentucky.

00:03:10.330 --> 00:03:11.140
Go ahead, Harlan.

00:03:11.140 --> 00:03:12.598
CALLER: Hi, I'm Harlan
from Greenup.

00:03:12.598 --> 00:03:15.352
I have an open-source project on
Google Code, and I want to

00:03:15.352 --> 00:03:17.944
hide it until it's totally ready
to take over the world.

00:03:17.944 --> 00:03:19.402
How can I do that?

00:03:19.402 --> 00:03:21.346
Oh, I also need to wipe
all the history

00:03:21.346 --> 00:03:22.318
before revealing it.

00:03:22.318 --> 00:03:24.280
Can you tell me how
to do that?

00:03:24.280 --> 00:03:27.820
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN: So Harlan
wants to hide his source code

00:03:27.820 --> 00:03:29.030
before it's ready.

00:03:29.030 --> 00:03:29.740
Until it's ready.

00:03:29.740 --> 00:03:31.700
BRIAN FITZPATRICK: Well, Harlan,
why do you want to

00:03:31.700 --> 00:03:33.246
hide all of your history?

00:03:33.246 --> 00:03:34.198
CALLER: Well, I don't know.

00:03:34.198 --> 00:03:36.221
I don't want people to see all
the screw-ups I made when I

00:03:36.221 --> 00:03:37.890
was starting out.

00:03:37.890 --> 00:03:39.620
BRIAN FITZPATRICK: Well, that's
understandable right?

00:03:39.620 --> 00:03:42.060
You don't want people to see a
lot of the mistakes you make

00:03:42.060 --> 00:03:42.380
in that sort of thing.

00:03:42.380 --> 00:03:44.870
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN: And we all
make mistakes as we work.

00:03:44.870 --> 00:03:47.880
The problem is, it's easy
to take it too far.

00:03:47.880 --> 00:03:48.620
Right?

00:03:48.620 --> 00:03:51.260
So everyone's a little bit
insecure to some degree.

00:03:51.260 --> 00:03:53.590
And part of it is the fact that
we have this concept in

00:03:53.590 --> 00:03:57.110
our head of people doing
miraculous things with

00:03:57.110 --> 00:03:57.840
software development.

00:03:57.840 --> 00:04:00.430
That someone like Linus Torvalds
just woke up one day,

00:04:00.430 --> 00:04:02.250
and the Linux kernel sprung
out of his head,

00:04:02.250 --> 00:04:03.145
fully formed, right?

00:04:03.145 --> 00:04:05.000
And I want to be
just like that.

00:04:05.000 --> 00:04:07.990
And so maybe if I cover up my
mistakes, everyone will

00:04:07.990 --> 00:04:09.470
realize what a genius I am.

00:04:09.470 --> 00:04:09.760
BRIAN FITZPATRICK: Right.

00:04:09.760 --> 00:04:11.970
And there's a lot of heroes that
we have like that, right?

00:04:11.970 --> 00:04:15.260
And in reality, these guys, they
may be really good, and

00:04:15.260 --> 00:04:17.120
they may have done something
incredible, but they're

00:04:17.120 --> 00:04:18.430
mythologized to an extent.

00:04:18.430 --> 00:04:21.079
They don't necessarily deserve
every last bit of the credit

00:04:21.079 --> 00:04:21.829
that they were given.

00:04:21.829 --> 00:04:22.760
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN: They do
deserve a lot of credit.

00:04:22.760 --> 00:04:23.970
BRIAN FITZPATRICK: They
do, absolutely.

00:04:23.970 --> 00:04:25.050
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN: So I would
say, the thing that you

00:04:25.050 --> 00:04:27.760
should credit these folks
for aren't just--

00:04:27.760 --> 00:04:29.170
yeah, sure, they started
a project.

00:04:29.170 --> 00:04:33.760
They may not have done the
entire project by themselves,

00:04:33.760 --> 00:04:35.000
but they actually led a team.

00:04:35.000 --> 00:04:37.830
They created a team, they
organized a team, and started

00:04:37.830 --> 00:04:39.700
something big, and coordinated
something big.

00:04:39.700 --> 00:04:41.280
And so it had a huge impact.

00:04:41.280 --> 00:04:44.700
So I think the moral here is
that you should be thinking

00:04:44.700 --> 00:04:47.780
about, how do you work with a
team, not how do I present

00:04:47.780 --> 00:04:49.120
myself as a genius.

00:04:49.120 --> 00:04:49.640
BRIAN FITZPATRICK: Right.

00:04:49.640 --> 00:04:50.880
You don't have to hide
all your mistakes.

00:04:50.880 --> 00:04:51.550
Mistakes are OK.

00:04:51.550 --> 00:04:53.130
Everybody makes mistakes.

00:04:53.130 --> 00:04:54.520
Let's move to our next caller.

00:04:54.520 --> 00:04:57.188
We have Dan from Albuquerque.

00:04:57.188 --> 00:04:57.676
CALLER: Hi.

00:04:57.676 --> 00:05:00.604
I've been working on this
amazing piece of code for a

00:05:00.604 --> 00:05:03.532
month and a half, and my
co-workers keep bugging me to

00:05:03.532 --> 00:05:05.484
show them what I've
got done so far.

00:05:05.484 --> 00:05:08.412
I totally know they're just
going to slow me down.

00:05:08.412 --> 00:05:12.340
How do I get them to leave
me alone so I can code?

00:05:12.340 --> 00:05:12.703
BRIAN FITZPATRICK: OK.

00:05:12.703 --> 00:05:17.180
So he wants to live in a cave by
himself and write code, and

00:05:17.180 --> 00:05:18.670
just show up with this sort
of finished product.

00:05:18.670 --> 00:05:19.620
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN: Well, he
sounds like he's worried about

00:05:19.620 --> 00:05:21.960
being slowed down
by other people.

00:05:21.960 --> 00:05:22.120
BRIAN FITZPATRICK: Right.

00:05:22.120 --> 00:05:25.170
But you can be making really
great progress super fast, but

00:05:25.170 --> 00:05:27.950
if you're doing the wrong
thing, this isn't

00:05:27.950 --> 00:05:28.710
really worth it, right?

00:05:28.710 --> 00:05:31.300
So if you're working with other
folks, you need to sort

00:05:31.300 --> 00:05:34.230
of have that interaction, that
tight feedback loop.

00:05:34.230 --> 00:05:38.130
When you're writing code, you
don't write 10,000 lines of

00:05:38.130 --> 00:05:39.115
code and then hit Compile.

00:05:39.115 --> 00:05:40.240
Does anybody here do that?

00:05:40.240 --> 00:05:41.350
Because I don't do that.

00:05:41.350 --> 00:05:42.410
I don't think you do that.

00:05:42.410 --> 00:05:43.890
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN: You have
a tight feedback loop.

00:05:43.890 --> 00:05:44.100
BRIAN FITZPATRICK: Right.

00:05:44.100 --> 00:05:45.650
You write some code and
you compile it.

00:05:45.650 --> 00:05:47.370
Then you write some code
and you compile it.

00:05:47.370 --> 00:05:48.770
Same way with your team.

00:05:48.770 --> 00:05:51.790
You write some code and you get
some feedback on not just

00:05:51.790 --> 00:05:54.210
the style of what you wrote, but
the design of your code,

00:05:54.210 --> 00:05:54.680
and that sort of thing.

00:05:54.680 --> 00:05:54.980
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN:
That's all right.

00:05:54.980 --> 00:05:58.100
The question is, any project
needs to be in a tight

00:05:58.100 --> 00:06:01.140
feedback loop of, are you
working on the right thing?

00:06:01.140 --> 00:06:02.270
Are you solving the
right problems?

00:06:02.270 --> 00:06:03.850
Did you make the right choice?

00:06:03.850 --> 00:06:06.500
If you go too far without
getting any feedback, you may

00:06:06.500 --> 00:06:08.870
wake up and discover you've
created something that's

00:06:08.870 --> 00:06:11.075
redundant, or you made
a bad design decision

00:06:11.075 --> 00:06:12.430
that you can't undo.

00:06:12.430 --> 00:06:15.520
So there's a high risk to
working alone for too long.

00:06:15.520 --> 00:06:16.400
BRIAN FITZPATRICK: There's
also, it's a

00:06:16.400 --> 00:06:17.890
low bus factor, right?

00:06:17.890 --> 00:06:20.160
If this person in the cave gets
hit by a bus, or giant

00:06:20.160 --> 00:06:23.980
rock falls and covers the
entrance of the cave, nobody

00:06:23.980 --> 00:06:27.430
can pick up that bit
of code, right?

00:06:27.430 --> 00:06:29.240
But more than anything, I think
there's just a risk of

00:06:29.240 --> 00:06:30.670
wasting time.

00:06:30.670 --> 00:06:33.030
It's one thing to sit down and
write a whole bunch of code.

00:06:33.030 --> 00:06:34.670
But if it's not the right code,
it doesn't matter how

00:06:34.670 --> 00:06:35.600
much you get written.

00:06:35.600 --> 00:06:36.510
Right?

00:06:36.510 --> 00:06:38.130
Great.

00:06:38.130 --> 00:06:39.100
All right, let's take
a new question.

00:06:39.100 --> 00:06:41.464
We have Bill from Peoria.

00:06:41.464 --> 00:06:44.308
CALLER: I was wondering how you
guys feel about the social

00:06:44.308 --> 00:06:47.942
issues implied by the use of
mitichlorians in Star Wars:

00:06:47.942 --> 00:06:50.670
The Phantom Menace.

00:06:50.670 --> 00:06:52.570
BRIAN FITZPATRICK: I
think there's only

00:06:52.570 --> 00:06:54.420
three Star Wars movies.

00:06:54.420 --> 00:06:55.670
Sorry.

00:06:59.330 --> 00:07:01.960
Let's take some calls about
working with your team.

00:07:01.960 --> 00:07:02.770
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN:
Stay on topic?

00:07:02.770 --> 00:07:03.040
BRIAN FITZPATRICK: Yeah.

00:07:03.040 --> 00:07:05.340
Problems with working your
teammates, concerns about,

00:07:05.340 --> 00:07:07.900
that sort of thing.

00:07:07.900 --> 00:07:10.217
So we've got Sarah
from Wilmington.

00:07:10.217 --> 00:07:13.199
CALLER: Hey there,
I love you guys!

00:07:13.199 --> 00:07:14.690
We have got a new team leader.

00:07:14.690 --> 00:07:17.672
He wants us to write a freaking
mission statement.

00:07:17.672 --> 00:07:19.660
What the hell's with that?

00:07:19.660 --> 00:07:22.280
Can you get me an interview
at Google?

00:07:22.280 --> 00:07:25.145
BRIAN FITZPATRICK: Well,
Google is hiring!

00:07:25.145 --> 00:07:26.740
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN: So it
sounds like she doesn't like

00:07:26.740 --> 00:07:28.110
the idea of a mission
statement.

00:07:28.110 --> 00:07:30.580
BRIAN FITZPATRICK: Well, when
most people hear mission

00:07:30.580 --> 00:07:33.830
statement, you think of
smarmy, giant, big

00:07:33.830 --> 00:07:35.130
corporations saying stuff like,

00:07:35.130 --> 00:07:36.460
we're focused on focusing.

00:07:36.460 --> 00:07:37.420
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN:
We empower people.

00:07:37.420 --> 00:07:38.650
BRIAN FITZPATRICK: We empower
people to do the

00:07:38.650 --> 00:07:40.150
things that they do.

00:07:40.150 --> 00:07:41.850
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN:
Or Kumbaya.

00:07:41.850 --> 00:07:44.560
Hold hands, let's
have a mission.

00:07:44.560 --> 00:07:45.890
BRIAN FITZPATRICK: A mission
statement is actually, I

00:07:45.890 --> 00:07:47.300
think, really important
for a team.

00:07:47.300 --> 00:07:49.390
Because it's a way of
keeping you focused

00:07:49.390 --> 00:07:50.160
on what you're doing.

00:07:50.160 --> 00:07:52.500
It typically has got a direction
and a limiter.

00:07:52.500 --> 00:07:54.980
So you know we're going to go
this way, and we're going to

00:07:54.980 --> 00:07:57.420
do this, but we're not going to
do all these other things.

00:07:57.420 --> 00:07:58.810
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN: The limiter
is also important,

00:07:58.810 --> 00:07:59.300
like you say.

00:07:59.300 --> 00:08:01.030
It's not just about
what you're doing.

00:08:01.030 --> 00:08:02.930
It's also about what
you're not doing.

00:08:02.930 --> 00:08:03.885
That's just as important.

00:08:03.885 --> 00:08:07.110
Because it's very easy to sort
of have feature creep.

00:08:07.110 --> 00:08:10.060
And it's important-- well,
actually, you have a cool

00:08:10.060 --> 00:08:13.230
story about this, I remember.

00:08:13.230 --> 00:08:14.990
BRIAN FITZPATRICK: We worked a
lot of different projects at

00:08:14.990 --> 00:08:16.560
Google when we were
open sourcing.

00:08:16.560 --> 00:08:18.710
And there was one product, about
five years ago, that was

00:08:18.710 --> 00:08:19.430
going open source.

00:08:19.430 --> 00:08:21.920
And actually wanted to do their
development in the open.

00:08:21.920 --> 00:08:23.180
And I talked to them about
the importance

00:08:23.180 --> 00:08:24.090
of a mission statement.

00:08:24.090 --> 00:08:27.000
And the team lead was really
enthusiastic, and they got the

00:08:27.000 --> 00:08:29.210
whole team together
to do this.

00:08:29.210 --> 00:08:30.750
And a lot of people on the
team weren't really

00:08:30.750 --> 00:08:31.700
interested in it.

00:08:31.700 --> 00:08:34.320
But one of the things that
became really obvious quickly

00:08:34.320 --> 00:08:36.820
is that two of the tech leads
on the team actually didn't

00:08:36.820 --> 00:08:38.799
agree on what the product
was doing.

00:08:38.799 --> 00:08:41.390
And I mean, this isn't like
completely unusual here.

00:08:41.390 --> 00:08:42.580
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN: But nobody
realized it, right?

00:08:42.580 --> 00:08:44.000
BRIAN FITZPATRICK: They had
never actually codified what

00:08:44.000 --> 00:08:46.120
they were doing and what they
weren't doing and working on.

00:08:46.120 --> 00:08:48.660
So you know, years later,
I talked to this guy.

00:08:48.660 --> 00:08:50.660
I'm like, thanks so much for
supporting me when some of

00:08:50.660 --> 00:08:52.610
your team members weren't
excited about this.

00:08:52.610 --> 00:08:54.830
He's like, well, I thought it
was a waste of time, but I

00:08:54.830 --> 00:08:55.890
figured, what's an
hour, you know?

00:08:55.890 --> 00:08:56.940
We'll give it a try.

00:08:56.940 --> 00:09:00.520
But like he said, he discovered
really quickly that

00:09:00.520 --> 00:09:02.630
this was something that they
actually needed to do as a

00:09:02.630 --> 00:09:04.910
team to be more efficient,
to get

00:09:04.910 --> 00:09:06.040
everybody on the same page.

00:09:06.040 --> 00:09:07.130
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN: We
should point out.

00:09:07.130 --> 00:09:09.320
You should do more than just get
everybody to agree on what

00:09:09.320 --> 00:09:10.130
the mission is.

00:09:10.130 --> 00:09:11.500
You need to document it.

00:09:11.500 --> 00:09:14.750
If you simply all agree on what
something is, and it's

00:09:14.750 --> 00:09:17.100
not written down anywhere, it's
not on a web page, you

00:09:17.100 --> 00:09:19.850
will still find other people
coming in and arguing with you

00:09:19.850 --> 00:09:22.520
about it, or trying to question
what's going on.

00:09:22.520 --> 00:09:25.120
But if it's on a web page,
it's official, right?

00:09:25.120 --> 00:09:25.850
People get amazed.

00:09:25.850 --> 00:09:27.420
Oh, it's there on a web page!

00:09:27.420 --> 00:09:28.750
I guess it's real.

00:09:28.750 --> 00:09:30.190
BRIAN FITZPATRICK: So whether
it's a new person, an open

00:09:30.190 --> 00:09:32.560
source project, or someone
coming to join your team,

00:09:32.560 --> 00:09:33.990
they'll show up and they'll
ask a question.

00:09:33.990 --> 00:09:36.000
You respond by email, say, well,
this is why we do this.

00:09:36.000 --> 00:09:37.740
They will argue with
you for a week.

00:09:37.740 --> 00:09:40.140
But if you say, it's right on
this web page, which is maybe

00:09:40.140 --> 00:09:41.890
an easily editable wiki,
for all we know.

00:09:41.890 --> 00:09:43.520
They're like, oh, it's
on a web page.

00:09:43.520 --> 00:09:45.390
Somebody thought about
this, you know?

00:09:45.390 --> 00:09:46.460
Maybe we should move on.

00:09:46.460 --> 00:09:47.840
It's a very serious business.

00:09:47.840 --> 00:09:49.380
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN: But you
know, put it in the same place

00:09:49.380 --> 00:09:50.890
where you'd put your other
documentations.

00:09:50.890 --> 00:09:54.020
Your design decisions, your
goals, your failures.

00:09:54.020 --> 00:09:54.610
Right?

00:09:54.610 --> 00:09:57.210
You keep a trail of
documentation so people know

00:09:57.210 --> 00:09:58.940
where you've been and
where you're going.

00:09:58.940 --> 00:09:59.250
BRIAN FITZPATRICK: Right.

00:09:59.250 --> 00:10:01.380
So documentation, important
element of communication.

00:10:01.380 --> 00:10:03.010
Mission statements,
not all bad.

00:10:03.010 --> 00:10:04.500
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN: We
have another caller.

00:10:04.500 --> 00:10:06.140
BRIAN FITZPATRICK: We've
got Tom from Seattle.

00:10:06.140 --> 00:10:07.598
CALLER: Hi guys, this is Tom.

00:10:07.598 --> 00:10:09.542
I'm thinking about submitting
a proposal for

00:10:09.542 --> 00:10:11.000
Google Summer of Code.

00:10:11.000 --> 00:10:13.430
I found two projects that
look pretty interesting.

00:10:13.430 --> 00:10:16.103
One is super well-known, but I
poked around on their mailing

00:10:16.103 --> 00:10:18.896
list, and they were basically
all insulting each other and

00:10:18.896 --> 00:10:19.585
being jerks.

00:10:19.585 --> 00:10:22.641
The other project is more
obscure, but their committers

00:10:22.641 --> 00:10:23.635
seemed pretty cool.

00:10:23.635 --> 00:10:26.120
Which one do you think
I should go for?

00:10:26.120 --> 00:10:27.426
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN: All right,
so he's asking which

00:10:27.426 --> 00:10:32.310
Summer of Code open source
project he should join.

00:10:32.310 --> 00:10:33.610
BRIAN FITZPATRICK: Well,
Summer of Code.

00:10:33.610 --> 00:10:36.790
Everybody here knows Google
Summer of Code?

00:10:36.790 --> 00:10:40.200
Who has never heard
of Summer of Code?

00:10:40.200 --> 00:10:42.580
So Summer of Code is a way for
students to flip bits and not

00:10:42.580 --> 00:10:43.350
burgers in the summer.

00:10:43.350 --> 00:10:45.260
They get paid to work
on open source.

00:10:45.260 --> 00:10:47.630
That's a huge thing.

00:10:47.630 --> 00:10:49.380
Culture is really important,
though, and you can't really

00:10:49.380 --> 00:10:51.420
expect it to change.

00:10:51.420 --> 00:10:51.670
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN: Yeah.

00:10:51.670 --> 00:10:54.350
So what you'll find is a lot--
and this is not just true in

00:10:54.350 --> 00:10:57.570
open source, pretty much any
team in a corporation--

00:10:57.570 --> 00:11:01.350
you'll find that certain teams
are slightly dysfunctional in

00:11:01.350 --> 00:11:03.280
the way they interoperate with
each other, and some are

00:11:03.280 --> 00:11:05.320
really smooth and everyone
respects each other.

00:11:05.320 --> 00:11:07.800
And you don't see a single team
flip-flopping back and

00:11:07.800 --> 00:11:09.390
forth, week to week, between
those behaviors.

00:11:09.390 --> 00:11:10.850
They tend to perpetuate.

00:11:10.850 --> 00:11:14.340
And in fact, I guess you could
think of it as a culture, just

00:11:14.340 --> 00:11:15.570
like a yeast culture.

00:11:15.570 --> 00:11:16.020
It perpetuates.

00:11:16.020 --> 00:11:16.540
BRIAN FITZPATRICK:
Right, right.

00:11:16.540 --> 00:11:18.200
So we're in San Francisco,
home of

00:11:18.200 --> 00:11:19.570
fabulous sourdough bread.

00:11:19.570 --> 00:11:21.230
Go to any baker that
makes sourdough

00:11:21.230 --> 00:11:22.730
bread, and talk to him.

00:11:22.730 --> 00:11:23.790
How do you make your
sourdough bread?

00:11:23.790 --> 00:11:24.870
The first thing they're
going to put in

00:11:24.870 --> 00:11:26.780
there is the starter.

00:11:26.780 --> 00:11:30.990
So the starter is yeast and
bacteria that happen to get

00:11:30.990 --> 00:11:33.980
together and do some really
awesome stuff for bread.

00:11:33.980 --> 00:11:36.600
So they take this, and then they
put it into the new flour

00:11:36.600 --> 00:11:38.000
and whatnot, they make a loaf
of bread out of it.

00:11:38.000 --> 00:11:42.080
That starter culture inoculates
this loaf of bread,

00:11:42.080 --> 00:11:43.600
and you get more of
what you want.

00:11:43.600 --> 00:11:46.330
As opposed to, you know, the
bread just getting taken over

00:11:46.330 --> 00:11:48.930
by wild yeast and another junk
that gives bad taste.

00:11:48.930 --> 00:11:50.380
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN: And the
culture needs to be strong

00:11:50.380 --> 00:11:52.380
enough to resist other cultures
that may come

00:11:52.380 --> 00:11:53.210
floating by.

00:11:53.210 --> 00:11:54.160
BRIAN FITZPATRICK:
Right, exactly.

00:11:54.160 --> 00:11:56.910
So what we're saying is that
software developers are a lot

00:11:56.910 --> 00:12:00.220
like bacteria, right?

00:12:00.220 --> 00:12:00.420
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN: No.

00:12:00.420 --> 00:12:02.890
But what you start with
is what you get.

00:12:02.890 --> 00:12:03.260
Right?

00:12:03.260 --> 00:12:05.890
So if you start a project with
a few people who are all very

00:12:05.890 --> 00:12:09.220
respectful, and they trust each
other, and there's some

00:12:09.220 --> 00:12:11.190
humility, that tends
to perpetuate.

00:12:11.190 --> 00:12:14.630
They tend to attract more people
of the same behavior

00:12:14.630 --> 00:12:15.290
into the project.

00:12:15.290 --> 00:12:18.430
And if you start the project
with people being angry and

00:12:18.430 --> 00:12:20.440
screaming and one-upping each
other, that tends to

00:12:20.440 --> 00:12:21.470
perpetuate, as well.

00:12:21.470 --> 00:12:22.580
BRIAN FITZPATRICK: Right.

00:12:22.580 --> 00:12:25.240
Over the long term, you can
see projects go from more

00:12:25.240 --> 00:12:26.260
quiet to more aggressive.

00:12:26.260 --> 00:12:29.260
But you really see a project
go from aggressive to more

00:12:29.260 --> 00:12:30.570
peaceful and quiet.

00:12:30.570 --> 00:12:32.980
But so beyond that,
obviously, I think

00:12:32.980 --> 00:12:34.470
interest is really important.

00:12:34.470 --> 00:12:38.010
But you've got to find a style
that matches your--

00:12:38.010 --> 00:12:38.630
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN: Oh,
we're answering his

00:12:38.630 --> 00:12:40.880
question, that's right.

00:12:40.880 --> 00:12:41.600
Yes.

00:12:41.600 --> 00:12:44.030
Think about the culture that
you want to be part of, not

00:12:44.030 --> 00:12:45.300
just what project.

00:12:45.300 --> 00:12:46.810
BRIAN FITZPATRICK: So if you're
OK with the big rah-rah

00:12:46.810 --> 00:12:49.430
fight and aggressive culture,
then go for that.

00:12:49.430 --> 00:12:49.790
Right?

00:12:49.790 --> 00:12:51.130
So OK.

00:12:51.130 --> 00:12:51.350
All right.

00:12:51.350 --> 00:12:52.910
We have another caller here.

00:12:52.910 --> 00:12:55.760
Reginald from Schenectady.

00:12:55.760 --> 00:12:58.210
CALLER: I just hired a bunch
of really good software

00:12:58.210 --> 00:13:00.660
engineers for my project, but
they're not following

00:13:00.660 --> 00:13:01.640
directions the way I'd hoped.

00:13:01.640 --> 00:13:03.600
They don't really seem to
care about the product.

00:13:03.600 --> 00:13:06.550
How can I get them to
really kick ass?

00:13:06.550 --> 00:13:09.220
BRIAN FITZPATRICK: Well, OK,
Reginald, do they understand

00:13:09.220 --> 00:13:11.270
the vision of what you're trying
to do in your product?

00:13:11.270 --> 00:13:12.020
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN:
Are they excited?

00:13:12.020 --> 00:13:13.499
CALLER: Well, we've got a
product plan from the sales

00:13:13.499 --> 00:13:15.964
guys, and I told everyone
how important this is.

00:13:15.964 --> 00:13:18.132
It just seems like they're
ignoring my orders, no matter

00:13:18.132 --> 00:13:18.922
how much I yell at them.

00:13:18.922 --> 00:13:21.880
How can I get them
to listen to me?

00:13:21.880 --> 00:13:22.930
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN:
Well, clearly you

00:13:22.930 --> 00:13:23.580
need to yell at more.

00:13:23.580 --> 00:13:25.450
No.

00:13:25.450 --> 00:13:26.726
BRIAN FITZPATRICK: Beatings
will continue until morale

00:13:26.726 --> 00:13:27.960
improves, right?

00:13:27.960 --> 00:13:29.270
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN:
So the problem is--

00:13:29.270 --> 00:13:31.370
I mean, maybe this is
self-evident to a lot of

00:13:31.370 --> 00:13:33.850
programmers, but maybe not to
all managers, is that way to

00:13:33.850 --> 00:13:35.570
motivate people is not
necessarily to yell at them

00:13:35.570 --> 00:13:36.870
and bark orders.

00:13:36.870 --> 00:13:39.560
That may be good for factory
workers, may not be the

00:13:39.560 --> 00:13:41.960
greatest thing for knowledge
workers.

00:13:41.960 --> 00:13:43.660
Programmers want
to have turns.

00:13:43.660 --> 00:13:45.830
We talk about driving
the bus, right?

00:13:45.830 --> 00:13:48.140
They want to all feel like they
get a turn to drive the

00:13:48.140 --> 00:13:49.970
bus and have a stake
in the project,

00:13:49.970 --> 00:13:53.170
decide where it's going.

00:13:53.170 --> 00:13:54.690
BRIAN FITZPATRICK: If you give
them the opportunity to drive,

00:13:54.690 --> 00:13:57.090
and not just sit in the bus and
do what you tell them to

00:13:57.090 --> 00:13:58.480
do, they're going to
do a lot more.

00:13:58.480 --> 00:14:00.810
You're going to get a lot
more out of them.

00:14:00.810 --> 00:14:02.420
They could possibly do some
amazing stuff that you

00:14:02.420 --> 00:14:03.100
didn't think of.

00:14:03.100 --> 00:14:03.370
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN: Right.

00:14:03.370 --> 00:14:05.960
In which case, your role becomes
not barking orders,

00:14:05.960 --> 00:14:09.110
but instead, just removing
roadblocks so they can drive

00:14:09.110 --> 00:14:11.320
the bus whatever way makes
sense most to them.

00:14:11.320 --> 00:14:12.160
BRIAN FITZPATRICK: Right.

00:14:12.160 --> 00:14:15.380
We talk about sort of servant
leadership where your job as a

00:14:15.380 --> 00:14:18.160
leader isn't to bark orders and
yell at people what to do,

00:14:18.160 --> 00:14:19.900
but to sort of clear the road.

00:14:19.900 --> 00:14:20.450
Clear the path for them.

00:14:20.450 --> 00:14:21.010
Help them out.

00:14:21.010 --> 00:14:23.670
Get them what they need to
get their work done.

00:14:23.670 --> 00:14:24.590
So thanks.

00:14:24.590 --> 00:14:25.500
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN: There's a
lot more to say about that.

00:14:25.500 --> 00:14:27.000
Well, let's keep going.

00:14:27.000 --> 00:14:28.300
BRIAN FITZPATRICK:
So we have a call

00:14:28.300 --> 00:14:30.162
from Larry from Hartford.

00:14:30.162 --> 00:14:32.622
CALLER: That one guy who was
working in a cave before

00:14:32.622 --> 00:14:34.098
didn't want anyone to bug him.

00:14:34.098 --> 00:14:36.189
But you told him it's
important to

00:14:36.189 --> 00:14:37.050
work with the team.

00:14:37.050 --> 00:14:40.494
But surely, you can't do
that from the start.

00:14:40.494 --> 00:14:42.954
If he did, he'd never
get off the ground.

00:14:42.954 --> 00:14:45.168
What kind of hippie free
love crap are you

00:14:45.168 --> 00:14:47.650
guys dishing out here?

00:14:47.650 --> 00:14:50.230
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN: So he's
saying, if you start

00:14:50.230 --> 00:14:52.860
collaborating from day one,
you'll never get anywhere.

00:14:52.860 --> 00:14:55.280
Which is kind of true.

00:14:55.280 --> 00:14:56.190
BRIAN FITZPATRICK: If you
start too early--

00:14:56.190 --> 00:14:59.230
I mean, you can look at, what,
Google Code, GitHub,

00:14:59.230 --> 00:14:59.970
SourceForge.

00:14:59.970 --> 00:15:02.810
And there is just tons of
projects where someone comes

00:15:02.810 --> 00:15:04.370
out and says, I have
this great idea!

00:15:04.370 --> 00:15:05.520
And then nothing happens.

00:15:05.520 --> 00:15:07.690
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN: Here's my
readme file describing how I'm

00:15:07.690 --> 00:15:10.030
going to take over the world,
and nobody shows up.

00:15:10.030 --> 00:15:11.360
BRIAN FITZPATRICK: Or a bunch of
people show up and want to

00:15:11.360 --> 00:15:12.550
do a whole bunch of
different things.

00:15:12.550 --> 00:15:12.960
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN: Yeah.

00:15:12.960 --> 00:15:15.200
And they all argue forever, and
they never do anything.

00:15:15.200 --> 00:15:16.810
BRIAN FITZPATRICK: So that's
what too early looks like.

00:15:16.810 --> 00:15:18.080
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN: But if you
go to the other end of the

00:15:18.080 --> 00:15:21.040
extreme, the other end of the
spectrum, which is, if you do

00:15:21.040 --> 00:15:23.750
everything yourself, not only do
you have this risk of doing

00:15:23.750 --> 00:15:27.190
the wrong thing, but if you
just sort of reveal to the

00:15:27.190 --> 00:15:29.740
world something that's
mostly done, that's

00:15:29.740 --> 00:15:30.810
collaborating too late.

00:15:30.810 --> 00:15:32.690
And nobody wants to get
involved, probably

00:15:32.690 --> 00:15:34.060
because it's done.

00:15:34.060 --> 00:15:34.350
Right?

00:15:34.350 --> 00:15:36.360
Or there's no chance to
make a mark on it.

00:15:36.360 --> 00:15:39.580
BRIAN FITZPATRICK: Even if it's
not done, it's so far

00:15:39.580 --> 00:15:42.220
past the mark, I guess, that
people just aren't going to

00:15:42.220 --> 00:15:43.150
come and take your orders.

00:15:43.150 --> 00:15:45.195
There's not a lot of chance for
them to have an effect on

00:15:45.195 --> 00:15:45.530
what they do.

00:15:45.530 --> 00:15:47.120
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN: And you
see that sometimes with

00:15:47.120 --> 00:15:49.710
companies that take gigantic
products, open source them,

00:15:49.710 --> 00:15:50.990
throw them over a wall.

00:15:50.990 --> 00:15:55.150
Nobody comes because it's
finished and too hard to

00:15:55.150 --> 00:15:55.890
figure out.

00:15:55.890 --> 00:15:58.400
BRIAN FITZPATRICK: So I think
the real answer for Larry is

00:15:58.400 --> 00:16:01.420
design, prototype,
then collaborate.

00:16:01.420 --> 00:16:02.680
That's when you bring
other people in.

00:16:02.680 --> 00:16:05.020
Because you've got something to
sort of show and work with

00:16:05.020 --> 00:16:05.680
and chew on.

00:16:05.680 --> 00:16:07.330
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN: That's
a sweet spot, we call it.

00:16:07.330 --> 00:16:11.310
So if there is a prototype, sort
of a proof of concept,

00:16:11.310 --> 00:16:13.770
that's enough to show people
that it's not vapor.

00:16:13.770 --> 00:16:17.450
And it's still early enough that
people can get involved

00:16:17.450 --> 00:16:19.810
and feel like they have a stake,
but it's late enough

00:16:19.810 --> 00:16:22.810
that people aren't going to be
arguing about what to do.

00:16:22.810 --> 00:16:23.780
BRIAN FITZPATRICK: And that
doesn't mean you shouldn't

00:16:23.780 --> 00:16:26.890
talk to anyone about it.

00:16:26.890 --> 00:16:29.180
Talking to friends or something,
or getting advice

00:16:29.180 --> 00:16:30.510
from people, hey, what do you
think about this, and getting

00:16:30.510 --> 00:16:31.370
feedback is a good thing.

00:16:31.370 --> 00:16:33.770
But sort of opening the
floodgates for help and

00:16:33.770 --> 00:16:36.170
collaboration is what we're
talking about there.

00:16:36.170 --> 00:16:36.440
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN:
All right.

00:16:36.440 --> 00:16:42.080
So our next caller is Chromos
from Azjol-Nerub.

