CALLER: My girlfriend and I have
been playing Warcraft for

00:16:44.172 --> 00:16:46.265
seven years, but the last couple
raids, things have

00:16:46.265 --> 00:16:47.294
started to get rocky.

00:16:47.294 --> 00:16:49.230
I found out from her friend
she's been talking about

00:16:49.230 --> 00:16:51.938
joining another guild, and I'm
not sure my 25 men will be

00:16:51.938 --> 00:16:53.102
able to run anymore.

00:16:53.102 --> 00:16:56.010
What can I do to patch
things up?

00:16:56.010 --> 00:16:56.880
BRIAN FITZPATRICK: Is that
a Warcraft question?

00:16:56.880 --> 00:16:58.850
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN: I can tell
you that the Red Dragon

00:16:58.850 --> 00:17:01.620
Dynasty doesn't do any
recruiting at all, except in

00:17:01.620 --> 00:17:02.875
the realm forums, strictly.

00:17:02.875 --> 00:17:05.105
And if you see someone doing
that, you should contact one

00:17:05.105 --> 00:17:05.730
of the officers.

00:17:05.730 --> 00:17:08.180
But not during raid times.

00:17:08.180 --> 00:17:09.280
BRIAN FITZPATRICK: OK, thanks.

00:17:09.280 --> 00:17:11.650
So let's try and focus a little
more on topic here.

00:17:11.650 --> 00:17:15.460
Let's go back to the calls on
our teams here, please.

00:17:15.460 --> 00:17:17.470
Now we've got Vern
from Las Cruces.

00:17:17.470 --> 00:17:19.410
CALLER: Long time listener
and first time caller.

00:17:19.410 --> 00:17:23.918
I have a friend who has
a serious problem.

00:17:23.918 --> 00:17:28.270
He hasn't told anybody
about it yet.

00:17:28.270 --> 00:17:29.870
BRIAN FITZPATRICK: What
kind of a friend?

00:17:29.870 --> 00:17:31.465
Tell us more about
your friend.

00:17:31.465 --> 00:17:31.795
CALLER: Yeah.

00:17:31.795 --> 00:17:34.187
Well, he seems to be writing
less code lately,

00:17:34.187 --> 00:17:35.920
and advising my--

00:17:35.920 --> 00:17:36.910
his--

00:17:36.910 --> 00:17:38.395
teammates more and more.

00:17:38.395 --> 00:17:41.365
It's not like he's their
manager, but people keep

00:17:41.365 --> 00:17:43.840
looking to him to fix arguments,
and decide stuff,

00:17:43.840 --> 00:17:45.325
and give advice and things.

00:17:45.325 --> 00:17:49.290
Should I get him to see
a doctor or something?

00:17:49.290 --> 00:17:50.840
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN: Well, we
only look like doctors.

00:17:50.840 --> 00:17:54.410
BRIAN FITZPATRICK: Well, your
friend sounds like they're

00:17:54.410 --> 00:17:57.600
suffering from what we call
accidental manager, or

00:17:57.600 --> 00:17:58.720
leadershipitis.

00:17:58.720 --> 00:17:59.220
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN: So you
have this situation.

00:17:59.220 --> 00:18:01.990
And anytime you have a group
of people working together,

00:18:01.990 --> 00:18:05.090
even if there's nobody assigned
to be the manager or

00:18:05.090 --> 00:18:07.850
the leader, somebody will fall
into that role, whether they

00:18:07.850 --> 00:18:08.870
like it or not.

00:18:08.870 --> 00:18:11.340
They'll start advising
people, resolving--

00:18:11.340 --> 00:18:12.040
BRIAN FITZPATRICK: Well, it
might not be they'll go

00:18:12.040 --> 00:18:12.870
kicking and screaming.

00:18:12.870 --> 00:18:15.700
But they'll see a need, and
determine that I'm the person

00:18:15.700 --> 00:18:16.570
who's going to step into this.

00:18:16.570 --> 00:18:17.870
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN: It's not
necessarily a bad thing.

00:18:17.870 --> 00:18:19.710
I think it's just
human nature.

00:18:19.710 --> 00:18:20.720
There's a power vacuum.

00:18:20.720 --> 00:18:21.950
Somebody falls into it.

00:18:21.950 --> 00:18:23.790
And it's scary.

00:18:23.790 --> 00:18:25.970
If you call that
a manager, then

00:18:25.970 --> 00:18:27.080
programmers get very scared.

00:18:27.080 --> 00:18:29.730
Because the word manager
is a dirty word.

00:18:29.730 --> 00:18:32.820
We hear the word manager, we
think of pointy-haired Dilbert

00:18:32.820 --> 00:18:34.910
characters.

00:18:34.910 --> 00:18:36.660
Manager is a scary thing, which
is why we like to talk

00:18:36.660 --> 00:18:39.260
about leaders instead
of managers.

00:18:39.260 --> 00:18:41.060
People can be leaders without
being managers.

00:18:41.060 --> 00:18:43.170
People can be leaders without
having a title.

00:18:43.170 --> 00:18:43.500
BRIAN FITZPATRICK: Right.

00:18:43.500 --> 00:18:46.280
So the answer to Vern's
question, it's OK.

00:18:46.280 --> 00:18:49.700
And it's not a bad thing,
necessarily.

00:18:49.700 --> 00:18:49.880
All right.

00:18:49.880 --> 00:18:50.420
So that was good.

00:18:50.420 --> 00:18:51.720
Let's talk a little more
about leadership.

00:18:51.720 --> 00:18:54.020
Is there anyone out there who's
leading teams that has

00:18:54.020 --> 00:18:56.870
some questions?

00:18:56.870 --> 00:18:57.930
Scott from Bismarck.

00:18:57.930 --> 00:18:58.390
Go ahead, Scott.

00:18:58.390 --> 00:19:00.690
CALLER: We have a new manager
starting next week.

00:19:00.690 --> 00:19:02.300
I haven't met the guy yet,
but I want to get off

00:19:02.300 --> 00:19:02.990
on the right foot.

00:19:02.990 --> 00:19:05.434
Do you guys have any
tips for me?

00:19:05.434 --> 00:19:07.330
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN: So the
question is, how to get off on

00:19:07.330 --> 00:19:08.870
the right foot with
a new manager.

00:19:08.870 --> 00:19:12.150
BRIAN FITZPATRICK: Don't
wait around for orders.

00:19:12.150 --> 00:19:13.870
Basically, I'd say take
responsibility.

00:19:13.870 --> 00:19:16.860
If your team lead says, you
know, I want you to go in and

00:19:16.860 --> 00:19:19.530
look at a particular treatise
having an issue, don't just

00:19:19.530 --> 00:19:20.650
deal with that and come back.

00:19:20.650 --> 00:19:24.240
Go out in the forest and find
other similar issues, and come

00:19:24.240 --> 00:19:24.740
back, and say, look.

00:19:24.740 --> 00:19:26.590
I found this, and this is
what I'm going to do.

00:19:26.590 --> 00:19:28.660
I mean, I think the worst thing
to do is come back and

00:19:28.660 --> 00:19:29.800
say, what do I do next?

00:19:29.800 --> 00:19:31.730
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN: You're
saying, so, act like an adult.

00:19:31.730 --> 00:19:33.340
BRIAN FITZPATRICK: Oh,
well, that's crazy.

00:19:33.340 --> 00:19:35.670
But if you come to your manager,
or your leader, and

00:19:35.670 --> 00:19:38.410
you say, you know, this is what
I think I'm doing next.

00:19:38.410 --> 00:19:39.630
What do you think about that?

00:19:39.630 --> 00:19:41.370
As opposed to, what do
you want me to do.

00:19:41.370 --> 00:19:42.190
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN: So
there's a proactive

00:19:42.190 --> 00:19:43.530
communication.

00:19:43.530 --> 00:19:44.790
Don't wait for orders.

00:19:44.790 --> 00:19:47.090
Proactively pursue some
responsibility.

00:19:47.090 --> 00:19:50.230
Go out and figure out what you
think you should be doing.

00:19:50.230 --> 00:19:51.590
Don't just be a yes man.

00:19:51.590 --> 00:19:52.450
Have some opinions.

00:19:52.450 --> 00:19:54.480
Express what you really think.

00:19:54.480 --> 00:19:56.250
Tell your manager about
your roadblocks.

00:19:56.250 --> 00:19:57.580
Tell your manager about
your successes.

00:19:57.580 --> 00:20:00.310
BRIAN FITZPATRICK:
Communicate.

00:20:00.310 --> 00:20:03.030
Act like an adult, communicate,
and get your work

00:20:03.030 --> 00:20:03.450
done, right?

00:20:03.450 --> 00:20:05.860
There's a guy who started to
work with me few years ago,

00:20:05.860 --> 00:20:08.370
and he'd been in the industry
for like 20 years at this

00:20:08.370 --> 00:20:11.210
company, And the first day he
comes to me, and it's quarter

00:20:11.210 --> 00:20:13.060
to five, and he's like, look.

00:20:13.060 --> 00:20:13.790
I've got to leave early.

00:20:13.790 --> 00:20:15.600
I had an appointment that
I couldn't change.

00:20:15.600 --> 00:20:16.400
I'm really sorry.

00:20:16.400 --> 00:20:18.300
But I'll be here late tomorrow,
it's no problem.

00:20:18.300 --> 00:20:20.790
And I said, look, man, I don't
care when you come and go.

00:20:20.790 --> 00:20:22.620
As long as you put in your
85 hours a week,

00:20:22.620 --> 00:20:24.460
you're fine, right?

00:20:24.460 --> 00:20:25.810
And he's like, well, what am
I going to do with all

00:20:25.810 --> 00:20:27.930
my spare time now?

00:20:27.930 --> 00:20:28.520
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN: Poor guy.

00:20:28.520 --> 00:20:31.200
BRIAN FITZPATRICK: But
seriously, it's like it's, you

00:20:31.200 --> 00:20:32.440
don't need to stamp
a time clock.

00:20:32.440 --> 00:20:33.860
You know what your
responsibilities are.

00:20:33.860 --> 00:20:35.350
You know what you need to do.

00:20:35.350 --> 00:20:37.540
You know how much you need
to do to get it done.

00:20:37.540 --> 00:20:38.470
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN: Act
like a grown up.

00:20:38.470 --> 00:20:39.470
BRIAN FITZPATRICK: Exactly.

00:20:39.470 --> 00:20:40.440
OK.

00:20:40.440 --> 00:20:41.530
We have our next caller.

00:20:41.530 --> 00:20:43.140
Lance from Portland.

00:20:43.140 --> 00:20:44.108
CALLER: Hi, guys.

00:20:44.108 --> 00:20:47.012
Just like that other caller, I
work under a tight deadline.

00:20:47.012 --> 00:20:49.432
I need people to work
faster and longer.

00:20:49.432 --> 00:20:51.852
I've even threatened to fire
folks if they can't get their

00:20:51.852 --> 00:20:52.820
performance up.

00:20:52.820 --> 00:20:54.756
What's wrong with
these people?

00:20:54.756 --> 00:20:56.208
Why aren't they scared?

00:20:56.208 --> 00:20:58.650
Why aren't they getting
more done?

00:20:58.650 --> 00:21:00.330
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN: So he's
threatening to fire people

00:21:00.330 --> 00:21:02.460
unless they get their
performance up.

00:21:02.460 --> 00:21:03.580
Stick.

00:21:03.580 --> 00:21:04.865
Shake a giant stick.

00:21:04.865 --> 00:21:06.090
That doesn't work so well.

00:21:06.090 --> 00:21:08.030
BRIAN FITZPATRICK: Especially
not with engineering people.

00:21:08.030 --> 00:21:09.210
Engineering is a
creative thing.

00:21:09.210 --> 00:21:13.290
I think that it's not just
a matter of some rote

00:21:13.290 --> 00:21:15.670
activities.

00:21:15.670 --> 00:21:19.230
I think managers really came
into prevalence during the

00:21:19.230 --> 00:21:20.780
industrial revolution.

00:21:20.780 --> 00:21:22.290
You have your assembly line.

00:21:22.290 --> 00:21:25.770
You have your workers who are
stuffing cans with meat.

00:21:25.770 --> 00:21:27.820
And you know, you shake the
stick at them, you give them

00:21:27.820 --> 00:21:29.120
the carrot, et cetera.

00:21:29.120 --> 00:21:30.460
You want to get things
going more quickly.

00:21:30.460 --> 00:21:32.080
There's not a lot of independent
thought there.

00:21:32.080 --> 00:21:34.162
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN: But if I
shake a carrot or a stick at

00:21:34.162 --> 00:21:36.970
you, you're not going to be
smarter, necessarily.

00:21:36.970 --> 00:21:37.940
BRIAN FITZPATRICK: Or think
more creatively.

00:21:37.940 --> 00:21:39.300
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN: Think
more creatively now

00:21:39.300 --> 00:21:41.550
or I'll fire you!

00:21:41.550 --> 00:21:42.850
You need to nurture
people, right?

00:21:42.850 --> 00:21:47.180
I mean, really sort of help them
to get their job done.

00:21:47.180 --> 00:21:49.170
CALLER: So what am
I supposed to do?

00:21:49.170 --> 00:21:50.150
Coddle them?

00:21:50.150 --> 00:21:53.580
Offer them raises and bonuses
to meet their deadline?

00:21:53.580 --> 00:21:54.560
Kiss their asses?

00:21:54.560 --> 00:21:56.030
Fluff their pillows?

00:21:56.030 --> 00:21:57.010
You guys are useless.

00:21:57.010 --> 00:21:59.460
[DIAL TONE]

00:21:59.460 --> 00:21:59.950
BRIAN FITZPATRICK: Thank you.

00:21:59.950 --> 00:22:03.340
Thank you for calling.

00:22:03.340 --> 00:22:04.830
Either way.

00:22:04.830 --> 00:22:06.390
I think you need to give people
a reason to care.

00:22:06.390 --> 00:22:07.110
I mean, tell your--

00:22:07.110 --> 00:22:09.250
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN: Well, so
there's this great guy named

00:22:09.250 --> 00:22:11.910
Dan Pink who talks on the
internet and other places.

00:22:11.910 --> 00:22:14.720
He talks about, all right, well,
here's how to actually

00:22:14.720 --> 00:22:16.430
encourage people to
be productive in

00:22:16.430 --> 00:22:17.330
the knowledge industry.

00:22:17.330 --> 00:22:17.830
Right?

00:22:17.830 --> 00:22:20.740
You should give them autonomy,
mastery, and purpose.

00:22:20.740 --> 00:22:22.400
I love these three things.

00:22:22.400 --> 00:22:24.640
Autonomy means, treat them
like a grown up.

00:22:24.640 --> 00:22:27.175
Let them do their job the way
they want to do it, what makes

00:22:27.175 --> 00:22:28.070
sense for them.

00:22:28.070 --> 00:22:30.950
Give them some free rein
in making decisions.

00:22:30.950 --> 00:22:32.200
And trust them.

00:22:32.200 --> 00:22:35.930
Mastery means give them a chance
to improve themselves

00:22:35.930 --> 00:22:38.010
and learn new things so
they stay engaged

00:22:38.010 --> 00:22:38.880
and they stay sharp.

00:22:38.880 --> 00:22:41.220
You don't want to take your
sharpest knife and grind it in

00:22:41.220 --> 00:22:42.140
the sidewalk.

00:22:42.140 --> 00:22:45.350
You want to let the knife
sharpen itself.

00:22:45.350 --> 00:22:47.930
And finally purpose, meaning
you want to let the people

00:22:47.930 --> 00:22:50.960
actually feel like they have a
stake in what they're doing.

00:22:50.960 --> 00:22:52.510
Give them a reason to care.

00:22:52.510 --> 00:22:54.730
So it's really important
to them.

00:22:54.730 --> 00:22:55.860
BRIAN FITZPATRICK: To summarize,
I think there's no

00:22:55.860 --> 00:22:57.950
way that you can actually get
someone more motivated than

00:22:57.950 --> 00:22:58.950
they can motivate themselves.

00:22:58.950 --> 00:23:01.240
So give them the tools that
they need to do that.

00:23:01.240 --> 00:23:02.790
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN: Intrinsic
versus extrinsic motivation.

00:23:02.790 --> 00:23:03.890
BRIAN FITZPATRICK: Right,
absolutely.

00:23:03.890 --> 00:23:05.470
That's an excellent question.

00:23:05.470 --> 00:23:05.680
OK.

00:23:05.680 --> 00:23:07.980
We have Todd from Lisle.

00:23:07.980 --> 00:23:08.990
Go ahead, Todd.

00:23:08.990 --> 00:23:11.186
CALLER: I've got to say,
that last guy seemed

00:23:11.186 --> 00:23:12.894
like a total jerk!

00:23:12.894 --> 00:23:16.310
There's a guy on my team who
acts like that, too, almost

00:23:16.310 --> 00:23:17.790
all the time!

00:23:17.790 --> 00:23:20.582
How do you guys usually deal
with people like that?

00:23:20.582 --> 00:23:21.620
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN: That's
a good question.

00:23:21.620 --> 00:23:24.170
He's asking, how do we deal
with people who are jerks.

00:23:24.170 --> 00:23:25.920
BRIAN FITZPATRICK: Well, we see
this with people not only

00:23:25.920 --> 00:23:27.810
in your team, but outside
of your team, as well.

00:23:27.810 --> 00:23:28.900
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN: Which is
a good segue to the next

00:23:28.900 --> 00:23:29.440
section, right?

00:23:29.440 --> 00:23:31.550
Talking about working with
people closely who aren't

00:23:31.550 --> 00:23:32.850
necessarily on your team.

00:23:32.850 --> 00:23:33.140
BRIAN FITZPATRICK: Right.

00:23:33.140 --> 00:23:35.570
Well I mean, you need to protect
your culture, right?

00:23:35.570 --> 00:23:39.780
And the most important thing
that your team has is

00:23:39.780 --> 00:23:40.900
attention and focus.

00:23:40.900 --> 00:23:43.100
And what you're doing, you're
here to write software.

00:23:43.100 --> 00:23:45.670
You're not here to get in
a giant yelling contest.

00:23:45.670 --> 00:23:46.360
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN:
Although it's hard.

00:23:46.360 --> 00:23:48.390
Because people will
push your buttons.

00:23:48.390 --> 00:23:50.030
You'll want to have these
emotional reactions.

00:23:50.030 --> 00:23:52.776
If they're trolling you, or
they're just being mean in

00:23:52.776 --> 00:23:55.440
some way, you want to spend a
lot of energy fighting back,

00:23:55.440 --> 00:23:57.790
or hurting them back, and it's
easy to get carried away.

00:23:57.790 --> 00:24:00.530
And then you suddenly realize
you've wasted your whole day,

00:24:00.530 --> 00:24:02.480
you're emotionally drained,
you've not written any

00:24:02.480 --> 00:24:02.910
software at all.

00:24:02.910 --> 00:24:05.500
BRIAN FITZPATRICK: It's really
hard when someone verbally or

00:24:05.500 --> 00:24:07.200
in an email or whatever
attacks you,

00:24:07.200 --> 00:24:08.800
not to fight back.

00:24:08.800 --> 00:24:10.600
You want to give them that
little zinger that puts them

00:24:10.600 --> 00:24:12.190
in their place and all, but
typically, it's not going to

00:24:12.190 --> 00:24:12.620
affect them.

00:24:12.620 --> 00:24:13.430
They're going to keep going.

00:24:13.430 --> 00:24:15.660
So there's an old
Usenet adage--

00:24:15.660 --> 00:24:18.900
remember Usenet, around
about 700 years ago?

00:24:18.900 --> 00:24:20.650
Don't feed the energy
creature, right?

00:24:20.650 --> 00:24:23.470
And really, I think that's
really important.

00:24:23.470 --> 00:24:24.850
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN: We were on
an open source project for

00:24:24.850 --> 00:24:28.010
many years, and a rather famous
person came to the

00:24:28.010 --> 00:24:30.940
mailing list and said, oh,
this product sucks.

00:24:30.940 --> 00:24:31.990
It's terrible.

00:24:31.990 --> 00:24:33.040
What's wrong with you people?

00:24:33.040 --> 00:24:36.040
He was basically there to give
a bug report, but the email

00:24:36.040 --> 00:24:40.300
was full of just incredible
bile and insults.

00:24:40.300 --> 00:24:41.760
It was ridiculous, right?

00:24:41.760 --> 00:24:44.780
And I was so proud, because we
didn't actually respond.

00:24:44.780 --> 00:24:47.400
Somebody else in the open source
project responded with

00:24:47.400 --> 00:24:49.890
the most simple, formal
language, like, oh, looks like

00:24:49.890 --> 00:24:50.890
you found a bug.

00:24:50.890 --> 00:24:51.330
Thanks.

00:24:51.330 --> 00:24:52.760
Can you try doing
this instead?

00:24:52.760 --> 00:24:53.710
We're going to look into it.

00:24:53.710 --> 00:24:56.450
And of course, he responds back
with just more anger and

00:24:56.450 --> 00:24:57.850
bile, and [GROWL].

00:24:57.850 --> 00:24:59.520
And you know, every time
somebody else from our

00:24:59.520 --> 00:25:02.400
community just responds very
calmly, as if there was

00:25:02.400 --> 00:25:03.000
nothing wrong--

00:25:03.000 --> 00:25:04.530
BRIAN FITZPATRICK: We found
the bug and we fixed it.

00:25:04.530 --> 00:25:05.570
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN: But it's
funny, because the guy kept

00:25:05.570 --> 00:25:07.380
looking like more and more
of an idiot the more he

00:25:07.380 --> 00:25:10.300
responded, and the less we
responded to the bile.

00:25:10.300 --> 00:25:13.090
But we did find the bug.

00:25:13.090 --> 00:25:15.240
BRIAN FITZPATRICK: But if we'd
just tried to argue, we could

00:25:15.240 --> 00:25:17.210
have easily gone off into a
giant argument with the

00:25:17.210 --> 00:25:18.880
person, right?

00:25:18.880 --> 00:25:19.200
All right.

00:25:19.200 --> 00:25:20.470
That's excellent.

00:25:20.470 --> 00:25:22.960
We have Mark from Ann
Arbor on the line.

00:25:22.960 --> 00:25:23.450
CALLER: Hi.

00:25:23.450 --> 00:25:25.900
I've heard you guys give
this speech before.

00:25:25.900 --> 00:25:29.820
And as far as I can tell, it's
just a recipe for elitism.

00:25:29.820 --> 00:25:33.413
You talk about building
consensus-based teams, but

00:25:33.413 --> 00:25:35.700
you're just looking for
a bunch of pushovers.

00:25:35.700 --> 00:25:38.803
All you guys want to do is
screen out people who disagree

00:25:38.803 --> 00:25:41.240
with your team.

00:25:41.240 --> 00:25:43.700
BRIAN FITZPATRICK: He's saying
we're being elitists.

00:25:43.700 --> 00:25:44.260
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN: Well.

00:25:44.260 --> 00:25:47.510
Maybe he should go away.

00:25:47.510 --> 00:25:48.375
BRIAN FITZPATRICK: Well, I
think it's an important

00:25:48.375 --> 00:25:50.080
distinction to make here.

00:25:50.080 --> 00:25:53.000
We're not talking about throwing
the people out, or

00:25:53.000 --> 00:25:54.130
getting rid of the people.

00:25:54.130 --> 00:25:57.300
We're talking about addressing
the behavior.

00:25:57.300 --> 00:25:58.220
There's a huge difference.

00:25:58.220 --> 00:26:01.500
I mean, you can actually wind
up alienating really good

00:26:01.500 --> 00:26:04.400
people if you sort
of throw the baby

00:26:04.400 --> 00:26:05.080
out with the bathwater.

00:26:05.080 --> 00:26:08.790
We had one guy who was working
with us who was really an

00:26:08.790 --> 00:26:10.560
amazing engineer.

00:26:10.560 --> 00:26:12.600
But he pissed everybody off.

00:26:12.600 --> 00:26:15.490
He just constantly said things
that were insulting.

00:26:15.490 --> 00:26:17.650
He'd go along, work, work, work,
boom, say something, and

00:26:17.650 --> 00:26:19.570
people would be like,
what the heck?

00:26:19.570 --> 00:26:21.820
And so one of us, I
think it was you--

00:26:21.820 --> 00:26:24.720
You pulled him aside on chat
or something and said, you

00:26:24.720 --> 00:26:27.380
know, hey, do you realize that
when you do this, you're

00:26:27.380 --> 00:26:29.050
having this effect on the
rest of the team?

00:26:29.050 --> 00:26:30.630
And he was shocked, wasn't he?

00:26:30.630 --> 00:26:31.670
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN: I did
think he was surprised.

00:26:31.670 --> 00:26:34.070
But the point was, we didn't
say, get out of

00:26:34.070 --> 00:26:34.900
here, you're a jerk.

00:26:34.900 --> 00:26:37.430
We said, please behave
in a civil manner.

00:26:37.430 --> 00:26:39.500
I don't think you realize that
you're not being civil.

00:26:39.500 --> 00:26:39.780
BRIAN FITZPATRICK: Right.

00:26:39.780 --> 00:26:42.250
And I don't think he quite
realized it, but he cut back

00:26:42.250 --> 00:26:42.750
on the behavior.

00:26:42.750 --> 00:26:44.030
And things did smooth
out quite a bit.

00:26:44.030 --> 00:26:46.440
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN: Right And
so that's what say for people

00:26:46.440 --> 00:26:47.990
who are moderating mailing
lists, any

00:26:47.990 --> 00:26:49.130
kind of lists, right?

00:26:49.130 --> 00:26:50.865
It's not about who's
in and who's out.

00:26:50.865 --> 00:26:54.440
It's about what kind of behavior
is tolerated by

00:26:54.440 --> 00:26:56.220
anybody, whether they're
on the list or not.

00:26:56.220 --> 00:26:57.850
BRIAN FITZPATRICK: But on that
same note, you do also have to

00:26:57.850 --> 00:26:59.830
know when to flip
the Bozo bit.

00:26:59.830 --> 00:27:01.620
You get some people who
just don't understand.

00:27:01.620 --> 00:27:04.422
We did have one guy who wasn't
actually writing code, but he

00:27:04.422 --> 00:27:06.800
was really enthusiastic, and
really friendly, and he would

00:27:06.800 --> 00:27:08.750
answer other people's questions
all the time,

00:27:08.750 --> 00:27:09.680
incorrectly.

00:27:09.680 --> 00:27:12.045
He would also just sort of free
associate on the mailing

00:27:12.045 --> 00:27:13.930
list. Hey, did you ever think
about putting this in?

00:27:13.930 --> 00:27:14.640
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN: It
was like his stream of

00:27:14.640 --> 00:27:17.460
consciousness kept emailing
the list every hour.

00:27:17.460 --> 00:27:18.580
BRIAN FITZPATRICK: We should put
a list of Star Trek reruns

00:27:18.580 --> 00:27:19.300
in the documentation.

00:27:19.300 --> 00:27:20.700
You're like, what?

00:27:20.700 --> 00:27:23.430
And we actually talked to him
a couple of times about it,

00:27:23.430 --> 00:27:24.400
and he didn't quite get it.

00:27:24.400 --> 00:27:26.990
We finally sort of said, look,
you need to stop doing all

00:27:26.990 --> 00:27:27.440
this stuff.

00:27:27.440 --> 00:27:29.070
And he really didn't
understand.

00:27:29.070 --> 00:27:32.350
But he did agree to actually
stop posting about all this.

00:27:32.350 --> 00:27:34.080
That was one of the harder
things, right?

00:27:34.080 --> 00:27:36.090
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN: Well, I
think what that proves is that

00:27:36.090 --> 00:27:38.570
there could be people who are
disrupting your team's

00:27:38.570 --> 00:27:41.520
attention and focus who are not
trolls, who are the nicest

00:27:41.520 --> 00:27:44.710
people in the world.

00:27:44.710 --> 00:27:46.920
One example is just people who
are perfectionists don't

00:27:46.920 --> 00:27:48.640
realize they're being
perfectionists.

00:27:48.640 --> 00:27:51.920
And they can actually drain all
the attention and energy

00:27:51.920 --> 00:27:54.680
by never letting anybody start
because the design doc is not

00:27:54.680 --> 00:27:56.040
perfect yet.

00:27:56.040 --> 00:27:57.210
So that's an example.

00:27:57.210 --> 00:27:58.950
BRIAN FITZPATRICK: But to turn
all this around into a

00:27:58.950 --> 00:28:01.210
different way of looking at it,
it's really healthy and

00:28:01.210 --> 00:28:03.060
important to have a good
team ego, as opposed

00:28:03.060 --> 00:28:04.150
to individual egos.

00:28:04.150 --> 00:28:05.350
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN: I know
that's the Apache Software

00:28:05.350 --> 00:28:06.160
Foundation's--

00:28:06.160 --> 00:28:06.410
BRIAN FITZPATRICK: Right.

00:28:06.410 --> 00:28:07.810
Apache is about building
communities.

00:28:07.810 --> 00:28:09.540
If anyone has ever looked
through a lot of the Apache

00:28:09.540 --> 00:28:12.100
code, you rarely find
someone's name at

00:28:12.100 --> 00:28:13.870
the top of a file.

00:28:13.870 --> 00:28:15.650
This is a practice that
is very contentious.

00:28:15.650 --> 00:28:18.730
It's almost as contentious
as vi versus Emacs.

00:28:18.730 --> 00:28:19.870
How many people here use vi?

00:28:19.870 --> 00:28:20.860
Anyone?

00:28:20.860 --> 00:28:22.080
How about Emacs?

00:28:22.080 --> 00:28:23.250
All right, fight!

00:28:23.250 --> 00:28:24.500
No, I'm kidding.

00:28:26.570 --> 00:28:29.950
There was this one guy came to
our product who wrote a whole

00:28:29.950 --> 00:28:30.760
date parser module.

00:28:30.760 --> 00:28:31.860
It was a pile of code.

00:28:31.860 --> 00:28:32.390
It was actually great.

00:28:32.390 --> 00:28:33.570
It was pretty well written.

00:28:33.570 --> 00:28:35.270
When we went through and gave
him the code review.

00:28:35.270 --> 00:28:37.250
We said look, you know, here's
our style guide.

00:28:37.250 --> 00:28:38.110
You did great on
this and this.

00:28:38.110 --> 00:28:40.220
But take your name out of
the top of the file.

00:28:40.220 --> 00:28:42.040
We don't have anyone's names
in the source code.

00:28:42.040 --> 00:28:43.470
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN: It's
just project policy.

00:28:43.470 --> 00:28:44.680
BRIAN FITZPATRICK: We have other
ways of acknowledging

00:28:44.680 --> 00:28:45.320
people helped out.

00:28:45.320 --> 00:28:47.250
And he's like, no, I wrote
this code, I'm

00:28:47.250 --> 00:28:48.100
putting my name on it.

00:28:48.100 --> 00:28:50.630
And we went back and forth him
him, trying to explain, look,

00:28:50.630 --> 00:28:52.320
this isn't about trying
to take away credit.

00:28:52.320 --> 00:28:55.400
But I mean, where does
it stop, right?

00:28:55.400 --> 00:28:56.360
I wrote three lines of code.

00:28:56.360 --> 00:28:57.400
Do I get my name in there?

00:28:57.400 --> 00:29:00.020
You wrote ten lines of code,
but I rewrote them.

00:29:00.020 --> 00:29:01.420
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN: Or what
if I delete some code?

00:29:01.420 --> 00:29:03.670
Does that mean the
name comes out?

00:29:03.670 --> 00:29:06.100
BRIAN FITZPATRICK: It's just a
lot of wasted energy, right?

00:29:06.100 --> 00:29:07.830
There's other ways to
recognize people.

00:29:07.830 --> 00:29:08.900
You do want to recognize
people.

00:29:08.900 --> 00:29:09.870
It's very important.

00:29:09.870 --> 00:29:11.150
It's a way of increasing
intrinsic

00:29:11.150 --> 00:29:12.980
motivation, I would argue.

00:29:12.980 --> 00:29:13.980
But we wound up not
taking this guy's

00:29:13.980 --> 00:29:15.320
code, and he went away.

00:29:15.320 --> 00:29:16.710
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN:
Which is sad.

00:29:16.710 --> 00:29:18.200
But it's also one of those
cases where it was more

00:29:18.200 --> 00:29:21.070
important to preserve the
culture than to accept this

00:29:21.070 --> 00:29:23.100
one particular contribution.

00:29:23.100 --> 00:29:24.060
BRIAN FITZPATRICK:
Yeah, excellent.

00:29:24.060 --> 00:29:25.150
All right.

00:29:25.150 --> 00:29:29.246
We've got Norman
from Winnetka.

00:29:29.246 --> 00:29:31.230
CALLER: I've been a long time
listener, Click and Clack.

00:29:31.230 --> 00:29:34.206
You guys do just an absolutely
amazing job.

00:29:34.206 --> 00:29:35.694
Long time fan.

00:29:35.694 --> 00:29:37.182
Anyway, I've got this
[UNINTELLIGIBLE]

00:29:37.182 --> 00:29:37.678
cream.

00:29:37.678 --> 00:29:39.662
It's an '84.

00:29:39.662 --> 00:29:41.646
Yeah, so anyway, the
transmission makes

00:29:41.646 --> 00:29:43.630
this da, da, da.

00:29:43.630 --> 00:29:45.862
I've tried to fill it with
sawdust, but I just don't know

00:29:45.862 --> 00:29:47.112
what to do about it.

00:29:49.950 --> 00:29:53.190
BRIAN FITZPATRICK: Have you
tried rebooting it?

00:29:53.190 --> 00:29:54.876
That fixes a lot of problems.

00:29:54.876 --> 00:29:55.880
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN: Think
it's a wrong number.

00:29:55.880 --> 00:29:56.400
BRIAN FITZPATRICK: Yeah.

00:29:56.400 --> 00:29:56.590
All right.

00:29:56.590 --> 00:29:59.250
Well, let's go back
to working.

00:29:59.250 --> 00:30:01.800
Let's move on to people who work
with your product, right,

00:30:01.800 --> 00:30:03.480
as opposed to people
on your team.

00:30:03.480 --> 00:30:04.160
Users.

00:30:04.160 --> 00:30:06.180
Yeah, take a couple
of calls from--

00:30:06.180 --> 00:30:07.884
we have Carl from Kansas City.

00:30:07.884 --> 00:30:09.360
CALLER: I've been listening
forever.

00:30:09.360 --> 00:30:11.164
I'm on an open source project,
and it's been

00:30:11.164 --> 00:30:12.312
doing really well.

00:30:12.312 --> 00:30:15.264
And lately, a bunch of industry
analysts have been

00:30:15.264 --> 00:30:18.312
asking us for whitepapers,
and bugging us for

00:30:18.312 --> 00:30:19.776
interviews and things.

00:30:19.776 --> 00:30:24.168
Everything about our software is
up on the website, clearly.

00:30:24.168 --> 00:30:27.096
And the mailing list is archived
and everything.

00:30:27.096 --> 00:30:30.580
These analysts and reporters,
these guys just don't get it.

00:30:30.580 --> 00:30:33.247
How do we get them to stop
bugging us and read the same

00:30:33.247 --> 00:30:34.945
docs as everybody else?

00:30:34.945 --> 00:30:37.380
Have you ever had to deal with
these kind of people?

00:30:37.380 --> 00:30:38.720
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN: So the
question is about how to deal

00:30:38.720 --> 00:30:41.050
with industry analysts.

00:30:41.050 --> 00:30:42.150
Do they wear white coats?

00:30:42.150 --> 00:30:43.330
BRIAN FITZPATRICK: They don't.

00:30:43.330 --> 00:30:46.680
But they do expect you to do
a lot of work for them.

00:30:46.680 --> 00:30:50.050
So I was VP of public
relations for

00:30:50.050 --> 00:30:51.230
Apache for a while.

00:30:51.230 --> 00:30:53.290
And we would get analysts who
would show up and say hey, you

00:30:53.290 --> 00:30:55.860
know, we're doing this
enterprise report on blah blah

00:30:55.860 --> 00:30:57.900
blah software, can you get this,
this, this and this?

00:30:57.900 --> 00:30:59.320
Because they're used to going
to big companies and saying,

00:30:59.320 --> 00:31:00.140
give us all this stuff.

00:31:00.140 --> 00:31:01.710
And people go, yeah, right
away, here it is.

00:31:01.710 --> 00:31:03.680
Can I get you a cup of
coffee with that?

00:31:03.680 --> 00:31:05.130
Because they want them
to write good things.

00:31:05.130 --> 00:31:06.980
And then engineers, thinking
very logically, think, well,

00:31:06.980 --> 00:31:08.970
this jackass should go read
the documentation.

00:31:08.970 --> 00:31:09.600
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN:
Like everyone else.

00:31:09.600 --> 00:31:10.250
BRIAN FITZPATRICK: It's
all answered in the

00:31:10.250 --> 00:31:11.230
mailing list somewhere.

00:31:11.230 --> 00:31:12.490
Go search for it.

00:31:12.490 --> 00:31:12.930
Right?

00:31:12.930 --> 00:31:14.580
That doesn't fly so well.

00:31:14.580 --> 00:31:16.300
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN: Well,
programmers don't like

00:31:16.300 --> 00:31:17.970
anything to do with marketing,
I think.

00:31:17.970 --> 00:31:19.760
In general, they distrust
marketers.

00:31:19.760 --> 00:31:22.760
BRIAN FITZPATRICK: How many
people here love marketing?

00:31:22.760 --> 00:31:24.080
Other than the marketers?

00:31:24.080 --> 00:31:26.520
No, I'm kidding.

00:31:26.520 --> 00:31:31.200
But the point is, is that I
think perception is important.

00:31:31.200 --> 00:31:33.780
I could say perception is
nine tenths of the law.

00:31:33.780 --> 00:31:35.550
You could have a great
piece of software.

00:31:35.550 --> 00:31:38.120
If people don't know about it,
if you don't shine it up a

00:31:38.120 --> 00:31:41.580
little bit, you're not going
to do as well as you could

00:31:41.580 --> 00:31:41.970
have.

00:31:41.970 --> 00:31:43.390
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN: I think
also a lot of folks don't

00:31:43.390 --> 00:31:45.200
realize that it's possible
to do marketing

00:31:45.200 --> 00:31:47.030
without being slimy.

00:31:47.030 --> 00:31:47.810
BRIAN FITZPATRICK: No!

00:31:47.810 --> 00:31:49.470
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN: It's
possible, I mean, you can

00:31:49.470 --> 00:31:51.010
underpromise and overdeliver.

00:31:51.010 --> 00:31:52.110
Make that your policy.

00:31:52.110 --> 00:31:53.960
BRIAN FITZPATRICK: So if you've
got substance, it's OK

00:31:53.960 --> 00:31:54.890
to do some shine.

00:31:54.890 --> 00:31:58.320
I think where it comes into
problems is that people expect

00:31:58.320 --> 00:32:00.640
that you just get a lot
of shine, right?

00:32:00.640 --> 00:32:02.970
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN: All
shine, no promise.

00:32:02.970 --> 00:32:04.810
So what's the answer
to the question?

00:32:04.810 --> 00:32:07.080
I think the answer is play
the game a little.

00:32:07.080 --> 00:32:07.970
BRIAN FITZPATRICK: Play
the game a little bit.

00:32:07.970 --> 00:32:10.340
I don't think you have to
really, like, fall over to do

00:32:10.340 --> 00:32:10.910
everything for them.

00:32:10.910 --> 00:32:13.950
But you do need to, I think,
play a little bit along there.

00:32:13.950 --> 00:32:14.770
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN: Don't
discount it completely.

00:32:14.770 --> 00:32:16.110
BRIAN FITZPATRICK:
Right, right.

00:32:16.110 --> 00:32:19.070
So our next caller is Connor
from Galifrey.

00:32:19.070 --> 00:32:20.305
Go ahead, Connor.

00:32:20.305 --> 00:32:21.295
CALLER: My company
has the email

00:32:21.295 --> 00:32:22.780
addresses of all our customers.

00:32:22.780 --> 00:32:25.750
We got those mainly so we could
send out license keys.

00:32:25.750 --> 00:32:28.555
We promise not to spam our
users, but now some of our

00:32:28.555 --> 00:32:32.185
marketing guys are begging to
email the customers with--

00:32:32.185 --> 00:32:34.165
they call it the occasional
product update.

00:32:34.165 --> 00:32:35.896
I don't think it's worth pissing
our users off for a

00:32:35.896 --> 00:32:36.640
quick bump in sales.

00:32:36.640 --> 00:32:37.630
What's your take on this?

00:32:37.630 --> 00:32:40.070
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN: So the
question is, is it worth

00:32:40.070 --> 00:32:43.910
getting a bump in sales to
spam the users, I guess?

00:32:43.910 --> 00:32:44.885
Sounds like spamming to me.

00:32:44.885 --> 00:32:45.116
BRIAN FITZPATRICK: No.

00:32:45.116 --> 00:32:45.270
Next question.

00:32:45.270 --> 00:32:49.880
No, it's about trust, really.

00:32:49.880 --> 00:32:53.050
And it's interesting, because
we're in a different place

00:32:53.050 --> 00:32:56.380
than we were 15 years
ago, thank God.

00:32:56.380 --> 00:32:59.110
Nowadays, in the software world,
it's really easy to

00:32:59.110 --> 00:33:00.310
switch and try other software.

00:33:00.310 --> 00:33:02.480
People can use your
software easily.

00:33:02.480 --> 00:33:04.310
They can just as easily
try someone else's.

00:33:04.310 --> 00:33:06.630
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN: So having
a trust reputation, your

00:33:06.630 --> 00:33:09.140
company's reputation, how much
people trust you, is really,

00:33:09.140 --> 00:33:10.180
really important.

00:33:10.180 --> 00:33:11.530
And it's dangerous, right?

00:33:11.530 --> 00:33:13.040
We always say trust is
like a bank account.

00:33:13.040 --> 00:33:15.860
You can spend years building
up trust with your users.

00:33:15.860 --> 00:33:18.220
But one night in Vegas,
it's all gone.

00:33:18.220 --> 00:33:20.665
You blow it all, you blow
all the trust at once.

00:33:20.665 --> 00:33:22.570
It's very scary.

00:33:22.570 --> 00:33:25.410
And doing things like sending
spam, it's a slippery slope.

00:33:25.410 --> 00:33:28.200
It's a way to blow your
trust right away.

00:33:28.200 --> 00:33:29.770
BRIAN FITZPATRICK: Well,
I have an example.

00:33:29.770 --> 00:33:31.550
My grandfather managed
a Firestone tire

00:33:31.550 --> 00:33:33.080
store for 35 years.

00:33:33.080 --> 00:33:35.870
How many people in this
room own a car?

00:33:35.870 --> 00:33:36.710
Leave your hands up.

00:33:36.710 --> 00:33:38.380
How many people own
a car and have a

00:33:38.380 --> 00:33:41.400
mechanic that you trust?

00:33:41.400 --> 00:33:41.990
Wow.

