people gave him.

00:44:31.380 --> 00:44:34.840
Even though supposedly the app
was great, and it worked great

00:44:34.840 --> 00:44:35.900
on many phones.

00:44:35.900 --> 00:44:41.230
But still, really bad reviews
kept creeping up to the top,

00:44:41.230 --> 00:44:43.410
and so he just couldn't
take it.

00:44:43.410 --> 00:44:44.350
So he took the--

00:44:44.350 --> 00:44:45.490
BRIAN FITZPATRICK:
Was it a bad app?

00:44:45.490 --> 00:44:48.260
AUDIENCE: No, it was supposedly
a really good app.

00:44:48.260 --> 00:44:49.480
BRIAN FITZPATRICK: Competitors
trolling?

00:44:49.480 --> 00:44:52.940
AUDIENCE: So what are your
thoughts on that?

00:44:52.940 --> 00:44:58.560
How can a team that is probably
emotionally tied to a

00:44:58.560 --> 00:45:01.830
product they just made, and made
available for free, and

00:45:01.830 --> 00:45:04.830
then, you know, you keep getting
these bad reviews?

00:45:04.830 --> 00:45:07.220
I'm asking because it might
happen to me if I put out a

00:45:07.220 --> 00:45:10.010
product for free and keep
getting bad reviews.

00:45:10.010 --> 00:45:10.830
BRIAN FITZPATRICK: I
think there's two

00:45:10.830 --> 00:45:11.660
parts to this answer.

00:45:11.660 --> 00:45:12.630
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN: You
are not your code?

00:45:12.630 --> 00:45:13.100
BRIAN FITZPATRICK: Well, yeah.

00:45:13.100 --> 00:45:14.240
You're not your code.

00:45:14.240 --> 00:45:16.800
I mean, you've got
to be ready for--

00:45:16.800 --> 00:45:19.150
Ben and I worked on Subversion
years ago, right?

00:45:19.150 --> 00:45:20.400
Sorry about that.

00:45:22.750 --> 00:45:24.920
We've gotten past-- and people
are like, you know--

00:45:24.920 --> 00:45:26.850
we actually will joke because we
use Mercure, and I'm like,

00:45:26.850 --> 00:45:28.290
oh, yeah, whatever
with Subversion.

00:45:28.290 --> 00:45:30.610
Somebody's like, how can you
talk bad about your product?

00:45:30.610 --> 00:45:33.970
And we're like, you've
got to learn how

00:45:33.970 --> 00:45:35.490
let go and move along.

00:45:35.490 --> 00:45:37.580
So I would say, first of all,
you're not your code.

00:45:37.580 --> 00:45:41.620
But second of all, if they're
legitimate, you've really got

00:45:41.620 --> 00:45:43.810
to look to see-- are there
legitimate complaints there?

00:45:43.810 --> 00:45:47.600
If it's just people trolling,
or griefing, or just people

00:45:47.600 --> 00:45:49.670
complaining or whatever,
it's just noise.

00:45:49.670 --> 00:45:52.150
I mean, if it really is a great
product, I think you'll

00:45:52.150 --> 00:45:56.170
get more good reviews than
you will bad reviews.

00:45:56.170 --> 00:45:57.990
But if there really are
legitimate bad reviews there,

00:45:57.990 --> 00:46:00.790
you've got to look for
constructive criticism.

00:46:00.790 --> 00:46:04.450
Constructive criticism is,
in my opinion, gold.

00:46:04.450 --> 00:46:07.640
And that's why, actually, we
should move along to this.

00:46:07.640 --> 00:46:11.580
That's why I'm a huge fan
of getting feedback.

00:46:11.580 --> 00:46:14.520
So back to the SpeakerMeter
thing.

00:46:14.520 --> 00:46:17.590
Getting constructive criticism
is a way for us to improve and

00:46:17.590 --> 00:46:18.060
get better.

00:46:18.060 --> 00:46:20.670
We gave us talk a couple of
weeks ago, and we asked

00:46:20.670 --> 00:46:21.800
people, you know, what
can we do better?

00:46:21.800 --> 00:46:23.780
And I think we learned some
things, and I'm hoping that

00:46:23.780 --> 00:46:25.210
we'll get some more feedback
today that we'll learn.

00:46:25.210 --> 00:46:25.610
So that's what I would--

00:46:25.610 --> 00:46:27.050
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN: I was going
to say, the other wisdom

00:46:27.050 --> 00:46:30.710
is, in terms of dealing with
trolls, or people who are just

00:46:30.710 --> 00:46:32.410
criticizing for no reason--

00:46:32.410 --> 00:46:34.033
what was that saying,
the internet is

00:46:34.033 --> 00:46:35.410
full of crazy people?

00:46:35.410 --> 00:46:37.510
BRIAN FITZPATRICK: The world is
full of crazy people, but

00:46:37.510 --> 00:46:41.430
the internet, it's like they
all live right next door.

00:46:41.430 --> 00:46:42.110
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN: You
just have to learn

00:46:42.110 --> 00:46:44.240
to ignore the noise.

00:46:44.240 --> 00:46:45.860
That's just how the
internet is.

00:46:45.860 --> 00:46:47.277
BRIAN FITZPATRICK: The first
thing I recommend people who

00:46:47.277 --> 00:46:49.740
