I am the younger
guy coming in.

00:47:04.076 --> 00:47:06.974
And so to me, a lot of
management types are sort of

00:47:06.974 --> 00:47:08.782
gray beard tech guys.

00:47:08.782 --> 00:47:10.300
They grew up on Visual Basic--

00:47:10.300 --> 00:47:11.550
BRIAN FITZPATRICK: Hey, hey,
be careful there, buddy.

00:47:13.830 --> 00:47:16.570
AUDIENCE: And so to them,
I'm a maverick.

00:47:16.570 --> 00:47:17.672
To me, they're dinosaurs.

00:47:17.672 --> 00:47:21.310
And so there's a little bit of
head-butting with new tech.

00:47:21.310 --> 00:47:23.660
I want to do things,
do it live,

00:47:23.660 --> 00:47:25.090
document it, send it out.

00:47:25.090 --> 00:47:27.450
They want to test it for
two weeks, see what

00:47:27.450 --> 00:47:29.000
happens, stuff like that.

00:47:29.000 --> 00:47:30.740
What do you guys recommend?

00:47:30.740 --> 00:47:31.850
BRIAN FITZPATRICK: Sounds
like a culture conflict.

00:47:31.850 --> 00:47:33.470
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN: Again, get
another culture conflict.

00:47:33.470 --> 00:47:34.630
Well, here is the biggest
question.

00:47:34.630 --> 00:47:36.326
Is there respect going
both ways?

00:47:36.326 --> 00:47:37.000
AUDIENCE: Absolutely,
I'd say definitely.

00:47:37.000 --> 00:47:37.420
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN:
Absolutely.

00:47:37.420 --> 00:47:40.290
Then I think this is a
resolvable issue, right?

00:47:40.290 --> 00:47:42.330
If people have humility and
respect, and there's some

00:47:42.330 --> 00:47:44.420
mutual trust, then it sounds
like it's something

00:47:44.420 --> 00:47:45.480
you can work out.

00:47:45.480 --> 00:47:48.316
But again, it sounds like this
is a case where people need to

00:47:48.316 --> 00:47:51.820
sit down and talk about, well,
waht should our processes be?

00:47:51.820 --> 00:47:53.790
And if you want to change the
culture, that's fine, but you

00:47:53.790 --> 00:47:57.420
should be able to have a
discussion about that, and not

00:47:57.420 --> 00:47:59.650
have a series of conflicts
over it.

00:47:59.650 --> 00:48:00.960
BRIAN FITZPATRICK: But
it's hard sometimes.

00:48:00.960 --> 00:48:03.040
One of the interesting things
about documenting why you do

00:48:03.040 --> 00:48:05.290
things, is if you can go in a
little bit of detail, in some

00:48:05.290 --> 00:48:08.365
cases, you can show-- there's
often a lot of reason and

00:48:08.365 --> 00:48:11.160
wisdom behind some choices and
decisions that may seem not

00:48:11.160 --> 00:48:13.340
obvious or archaic.

00:48:13.340 --> 00:48:14.650
But if you can dig in
and be like, oh,

00:48:14.650 --> 00:48:15.550
that's why we do that.

00:48:15.550 --> 00:48:17.680
Or maybe it's because something
really bad happened

00:48:17.680 --> 00:48:20.060
in the past here, we're guarding
it a little more

00:48:20.060 --> 00:48:21.490
carefully an trying
to avoid risk.

00:48:21.490 --> 00:48:21.990
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN: So
it sounds like you're

00:48:21.990 --> 00:48:24.550
recommending research of the
existing culture before

00:48:24.550 --> 00:48:25.800
deciding to overturn it.

00:48:25.800 --> 00:48:26.850
BRIAN FITZPATRICK:
Yes, exactly.

00:48:26.850 --> 00:48:28.390
And really try and understand.

00:48:28.390 --> 00:48:30.130
I mean, that's one of the
biggest things to do when

00:48:30.130 --> 00:48:31.640
you're having a disagreement
with somebody.

00:48:31.640 --> 00:48:34.830
If you can really, really,
really strive to understand

00:48:34.830 --> 00:48:37.410
what their point of view is--

00:48:37.410 --> 00:48:39.710
especially if you're married--

00:48:39.710 --> 00:48:42.960
then it makes it a lot easier
to carry that conversation.

00:48:42.960 --> 00:48:44.322
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN: The more
you listen, the more you are

00:48:44.322 --> 00:48:45.210
listened to.

00:48:45.210 --> 00:48:46.345
BRIAN FITZPATRICK:
Yeah, exactly.

00:48:46.345 --> 00:48:47.477
So thank you.

