I mean, flat out.

00:51:18.120 --> 00:51:20.170
there's a lot of cases I know
where people had someone that

00:51:20.170 --> 00:51:22.670
worked with them, or worked for
them, who wasn't meeting

00:51:22.670 --> 00:51:23.770
expectations.

00:51:23.770 --> 00:51:25.990
And they don't say anything,
because they don't want to

00:51:25.990 --> 00:51:26.770
rock the boat.

00:51:26.770 --> 00:51:28.930
And that's exactly when you
should be rocking the boat.

00:51:28.930 --> 00:51:30.930
When you're most afraid
to rock the boat.

00:51:30.930 --> 00:51:31.930
So it's like, boom.

00:51:31.930 --> 00:51:32.700
That's when you start
communicating.

00:51:32.700 --> 00:51:35.570
If you just flat out say, look,
this is what I expect of

00:51:35.570 --> 00:51:37.200
you, and this is what
I'm not getting--

00:51:37.200 --> 00:51:38.683
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN: And here
are two or three examples of

00:51:38.683 --> 00:51:40.120
where I expected something--

00:51:40.120 --> 00:51:40.830
BRIAN FITZPATRICK: Two
exampels minimum.

00:51:40.830 --> 00:51:42.130
At least two.

00:51:42.130 --> 00:51:43.070
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN: Give
them hard data.

00:51:43.070 --> 00:51:45.310
Say, I expected X, Y,
and Z, and you gave

00:51:45.310 --> 00:51:46.380
me this other thing.

00:51:46.380 --> 00:51:48.450
And you did it two
or three times.

00:51:48.450 --> 00:51:50.370
So we're going to
have to either--

00:51:50.370 --> 00:51:51.820
BRIAN FITZPATRICK: You can at
least be sure, in that case,

00:51:51.820 --> 00:51:52.840
that they know it.

00:51:52.840 --> 00:51:56.200
Because quite frankly, they
might not know it.

00:51:56.200 --> 00:52:00.260
So I would say communication
there is pretty important.

00:52:00.260 --> 00:52:02.470
We can take two more
questions.

00:52:02.470 --> 00:52:03.470
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:52:03.470 --> 00:52:09.165
A while ago, you talked about
the ethical issues of, for

00:52:09.165 --> 00:52:11.100
instance, spamming people
and whatnot.

00:52:11.100 --> 00:52:15.230
And what would be the right
thing to do when the general

00:52:15.230 --> 00:52:19.140
culture of the place
seems to be skewed

00:52:19.140 --> 00:52:20.340
towards that direction?

00:52:20.340 --> 00:52:26.792
And you did mention that that
would cause financial damage

00:52:26.792 --> 00:52:28.970
in the long run, but I am
not the bean counter.

00:52:28.970 --> 00:52:32.120
I am just the engineer, and I
doubt that would be persuasive

00:52:32.120 --> 00:52:34.510
from my part.

00:52:34.510 --> 00:52:36.520
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN: That sounds
like a question of how

00:52:36.520 --> 00:52:39.860
does one engineer change an
entire culture of a company.

00:52:39.860 --> 00:52:41.570
That's a really hard problem.

00:52:41.570 --> 00:52:44.400
We get this question a lot,
actually, and our answer is

00:52:44.400 --> 00:52:45.720
usually, find a new company.

00:52:45.720 --> 00:52:46.450
BRIAN FITZPATRICK: Well, no.

00:52:46.450 --> 00:52:47.980
Wait, wait, wait.

00:52:47.980 --> 00:52:50.300
Our first answer is, is
that you can make

00:52:50.300 --> 00:52:51.990
attempts at this, right?

00:52:51.990 --> 00:52:54.890
Try to change what you can,
and look into it, and make

00:52:54.890 --> 00:52:56.350
attempts to ask people
about it.

00:52:56.350 --> 00:52:57.570
Have you thought about
it this way?

00:52:57.570 --> 00:52:58.320
But yeah.

00:52:58.320 --> 00:53:02.460
If you try and are unsuccessful,
you can just sit

00:53:02.460 --> 00:53:03.520
there and stew about it.

00:53:03.520 --> 00:53:04.420
You can learn to deal with it.

00:53:04.420 --> 00:53:06.660
Or you can get the heck out.

00:53:06.660 --> 00:53:08.370
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN: I find,
also, reaching out to other

00:53:08.370 --> 00:53:10.980
people in the company who feel
the same way, you can start to

00:53:10.980 --> 00:53:12.520
sort of build a movement
within the company.

00:53:12.520 --> 00:53:14.000
I mean, it's politics, right?

00:53:14.000 --> 00:53:16.905
But you can actually form a
movement within your company

00:53:16.905 --> 00:53:20.140
so that there's a single voice
saying, we don't like this.

00:53:20.140 --> 00:53:21.540
We think we should
change this.

00:53:21.540 --> 00:53:23.210
And the louder you become,
the more the dialogue

00:53:23.210 --> 00:53:24.200
is likely to happen.

00:53:24.200 --> 00:53:25.630
BRIAN FITZPATRICK: But do keep
in mind that companies aren't

00:53:25.630 --> 00:53:26.380
democracies.

00:53:26.380 --> 00:53:27.990
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN: They're
not democracies.

00:53:27.990 --> 00:53:29.010
But you can still
have political

00:53:29.010 --> 00:53:29.800
movement within them.

00:53:29.800 --> 00:53:31.330
BRIAN FITZPATRICK:
That's right.

00:53:31.330 --> 00:53:32.360
Alice's Restaurant.

00:53:32.360 --> 00:53:33.860
Go ahead.

00:53:33.860 --> 00:53:36.835
AUDIENCE: I work on a team
where there's another guy

00:53:36.835 --> 00:53:40.016
who's a very capable developer,
but he often holds

00:53:40.016 --> 00:53:43.175
his cards real close to his
vest, doesn't share things

00:53:43.175 --> 00:53:45.270
with the rest of
the team often.

00:53:45.270 --> 00:53:49.620
And furthermore, my boss looks
upon him with great favor.

00:53:49.620 --> 00:53:52.865
Do you guys have any tips or
strategies that you might

00:53:52.865 --> 00:53:56.320
suggest for dealing with
both him and my boss?

00:53:56.320 --> 00:53:58.410
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN: Well,
what's wrong with him holding

00:53:58.410 --> 00:54:01.100
close to his chest, that he's
not sharing, or he's not--

00:54:01.100 --> 00:54:01.592
AUDIENCE: Right.

00:54:01.592 --> 00:54:04.544
That often times, he
won't engage other

00:54:04.544 --> 00:54:05.490
members of the team.

00:54:05.490 --> 00:54:13.684
Or often times, he'll maybe
get that super-special

00:54:13.684 --> 00:54:16.872
assignment or whatever before
others are considered, that

00:54:16.872 --> 00:54:17.742
sort of thing.

00:54:17.742 --> 00:54:18.740
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN:
Interesting.

00:54:18.740 --> 00:54:20.570
BRIAN FITZPATRICK: That's
another hard problem.

00:54:20.570 --> 00:54:24.360
I mean, again, you can
give him data.

00:54:24.360 --> 00:54:27.730
Like with your boss in
particular, if we got more

00:54:27.730 --> 00:54:29.450
information, we could do more.

00:54:29.450 --> 00:54:31.470
But that tends to be one
of the things that's

00:54:31.470 --> 00:54:33.340
really hard to change.

00:54:33.340 --> 00:54:36.600
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN: If you can
quantify the impact of him

00:54:36.600 --> 00:54:40.640
not collaborating with people,
then you'd have an argument to

00:54:40.640 --> 00:54:42.870
make, saying, well, we should
get him to open up.

00:54:42.870 --> 00:54:45.110
That gives us an argument to the
manager, right, or other

00:54:45.110 --> 00:54:46.020
members of the team.

00:54:46.020 --> 00:54:47.190
BRIAN FITZPATRICK: But if the
manager and the lead both

00:54:47.190 --> 00:54:50.370
think this is the way we're
going to run things, you don't

00:54:50.370 --> 00:54:53.000
have much of a way
to change that.

00:54:53.000 --> 00:54:56.340
It's really hard, because
they're defining the culture

00:54:56.340 --> 00:54:58.450
top down, and you're just
sort of following along.

00:55:01.400 --> 00:55:02.830
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN: Also, if
I were on the team, I would

00:55:02.830 --> 00:55:05.670
also try to figure out the
psychology of this person.

00:55:05.670 --> 00:55:07.190
Are they just insecure?

00:55:07.190 --> 00:55:10.680
Or are they egotistical?

00:55:10.680 --> 00:55:11.780
What's going on, right?

00:55:11.780 --> 00:55:13.240
How do you get them open up?

00:55:13.240 --> 00:55:17.280
And there may be the social
route, social engineering, to

00:55:17.280 --> 00:55:19.380
get in there and get them to
open up, figure out what's

00:55:19.380 --> 00:55:20.706
really going on.

00:55:20.706 --> 00:55:21.720
AUDIENCE: Sure.

00:55:21.720 --> 00:55:21.985
Thank you.

00:55:21.985 --> 00:55:22.610
BRIAN FITZPATRICK: All right.

00:55:22.610 --> 00:55:23.510
Thank you all for coming.

00:55:23.510 --> 00:55:24.360
We appreciate it.

00:55:24.360 --> 00:55:27.140
We'll be around for a bit,
talking a little more.

